          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-832242?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">中国两年来首次陷入通货紧缩。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：马克·R·克里斯蒂诺/Shutterstock </p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001121031"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline">作者： <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/stella-yifan-xie" itemprop="url" rel="author">谢一凡</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 8 月 9 日上午 5:21 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/china-slips-into-deflation-in-warning-sign-for-world-economy-bbefb179"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p>香港——世界第二大经济体的消费需求不温不火，经济担忧加剧，使中国两年来首次陷入通货紧缩，这给北京带来了更大的压力，要求其采取更积极的行动，以避免经济困境加深。</p><p>去年年底取消Covid-19大流行限制后，中国并没有经历价格飙升，而是一系列商品的价格出现了不寻常的下跌，从钢铁和煤炭等大宗商品到日常必需品和消费品，例如蔬菜和家用电器。</p><p>中国的经济困境与美国和其他发达西方经济体<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/while-everyone-else-fights-inflation-chinas-deflation-fears-deepen-4045cabf?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noopener">形成鲜明对比</a>，美国和其他发达西方经济体在解除新冠限制后通胀飙升，导致包括美联储在内的各国央行采取激进的加息方式，旨在在不影响经济的情况下给经济降温。引发经济衰退。</p><p>虽然随着中国出口产品变得更便宜，中国价格下跌可能有助于缓解其他地方的通胀压力，但它们可能成为全球经济的另一个担忧的根源。例如，大量低价中国商品可能会挤压其他国家生产商的利润并损害就业机会。</p><p> 7月份中国居民消费价格同比下降0.3%。美国最新数据显示， <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/consumer-price-index-report-june-inflation-ede7f4b1?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noopener">6 月份消费者价格同比上涨 3%</a> ，为两年多以来最慢涨幅，而欧盟年度通胀率为 6.4%，低于 5 月份的 7.1%。</p><p>对于中国来说，通胀的缺失反映出经济的不平衡，其特点是供给充足，而内需却处于休眠状态，经济学家表示，北京必须采取更多措施来唤醒内需。</p><p>但这种反弹很快就<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/chinas-economy-stutters-forward-as-growth-concerns-linger-1be8acb2?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noopener">消失了</a>。与此同时，由于<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/xi-china-economy-capital-investment-3439d31a?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noopener">与西方经济体的地缘政治紧张局势加剧</a>以及针对中国一些最赚钱行业的监管打压，私营企业的投资降至疫情前的水平以下。</p><p>与此同时，青年失业率<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/china-youth-unemployment-xi-jobs-522028c5?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">飙升至一系列历史新高</a>，6 月份达到 21.3%。随着西方世界的需求枯竭，作为新冠疫情期间的经济支柱的中国出口现在正<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/chinese-exports-fall-at-steepest-pace-since-february-2020-e930246b?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noopener">以多年来最快的速度下降</a>。</p><p>目前，中国决策者对物价下跌持乐观态度，否认通货紧缩将持续的说法。中国央行今年已多次降息，但财政和货币政策制定者都没有推出任何更大规模的刺激措施，部分原因是债务水平上升等限制。</p><p> “现实看起来越来越严峻，”康奈尔大学贸易政策和经济学教授、国际货币基金组织中国部前负责人埃斯瓦尔·普拉萨德(Eswar Prasad)表示。 “政府淡化通货紧缩和增长停滞风险的做法可能会适得其反，使经济摆脱螺旋式下降的难度加大。” </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><img width="600" height="800" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-832305?width=600" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p>中国国家统计局公布的数据显示，自去年10月以来，出厂价格同比下降，7月份出厂价格同比下降4.4%，降幅较6月份的5.4%收窄。周三。</p><p>但标志着更大转变的是消费者价格通胀，尽管生产者价格转为负值，但消费者价格通胀仍保持正值。继 6 月持平后，上个月下降 0.3%，这是自 2021 年 2 月以来的首次下降，与大流行初期（当时供应链和食品价格混乱）相比，这一读数与去年同期相比有所偏差。</p><p>除了2020年11月疫情对经济造成冲击之外，自2009年全球金融危机最严重时期以来，消费者价格和生产者价格从未同时处于通缩区域。</p><p>中国国家统计局发言人周三表示，7月份消费者价格通缩主要是由于食品价格较上年同期下降，去年食品价格因<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/china-extends-power-curbs-amid-heat-wave-drought-11661171568?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noopener">极端天气条件</a>而推高。中国人的主食猪肉价格 7 月份同比下跌 26%。上个月蔬菜价格也有所下降。</p><p>剔除波动较大的食品和能源价格，所谓的核心通胀率从 6 月份的 0.4% 升至 7 月份的 0.8%，为 1 月份以来的最高水平。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=E87CB6AE-077A-4221-86C2-EE6981C09C4C&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fchina-slips-into-deflation-in-warning-sign-for-world-economy-bbefb179&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption">美国生产的玉米比任何其他作物都多，去年美国农场向中国出售了价值 53 亿美元的玉米。但中国多年来一直在吸引其他生产商，并且正在探索实现长期自给自足的方法。插图：赵安妮<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div><p>即便如此，经济学家表示，今年消费者通胀也不太可能大幅上升。原因是消费者信心，或者更确切地说是缺乏信心，因为家庭继续感受到三年来新冠疫情的不确定性、监管的不确定性以及对房地产市场健康状况的持续担忧所带来的挥之不去的影响。房地产行业是中国几十年来经济增长的主要推动力之一，但目前却陷入了深深的恐慌，本周<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/country-garden-chinas-largest-surviving-developer-sinks-into-debt-crisis-2a525173?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noopener">围绕中国最大房地产开发商之一的默认担忧</a>引发了新的担忧。</p><p>与许多西方国家不同的是，政府在疫情期间向消费者发放现金，推动了家具和个人电子产品等实物商品的消费热潮，但北京迄今为止尚未向其家庭提供此类直接支持。</p><p>魏耀表示，除此之外， <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/chinas-property-market-enters-troubling-new-phase-1fe3143d?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noopener">房地产市场的重新低迷</a>抑制了中国消费者的消费欲望，因为许多家庭将公寓作为主要的财富储存手段，对房价波动高度敏感。法国兴业银行中国经济学家。</p><p> “问题是目前没有明显的电力恢复驱动因素，”她说。</p><p>王雷说，除了装修两年前购买的一套公寓外，他和妻子的总体支出与去年相比有所下降。看到同事和朋友被解雇，他感到害怕，开始控制任何不必要的开支。</p><p> “现在最好多存一点，谨慎一点，”40 岁的王说，他在北京一家视频游戏公司工作。 “经济前景并不确定。”</p><p>即使消费者价格开始再次回升，中国工厂主和出口商也可能在一段时间内与定价权作斗争，从而侵蚀他们的利润率，并损害他们扩大生产或雇用更多工人的意愿。</p><p>尽管 7 月份生产者价格通缩有所缓解，但 4.4% 的降幅仍低于《华尔街日报》调查的经济学家预期的 4.1%。</p><p>疫情期间，中国许多工厂提高产量，以适应​​海外订单的激增。现在，随着西方需求的衰退，汽车、消费品和其他产品的生产商面临库存过剩的困境，迫使许多公司大幅降价以减少库存。</p><p>一家总部位于中国南方城市深圳的机器人吸尘器制造商正寻求扩大海外销量，部分原因是国内竞争对手提供更便宜的选择，而消费者需求复苏缓慢削弱了国内销售，公司高管表示。</p><p>中国决策者面临的最终挑战是如何防止价格下跌导致产量减少、工资下降和需求抑制的自我强化螺旋。</p><p>经济学家预计中国央行将在未来几个月进一步降低利率，但许多人对仅靠此类举措能否消除通缩压力持怀疑态度。</p><p>这是因为<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/chinas-stimulus-pivot-is-prompted-by-fears-slowing-growth-could-worsen-5d35d34?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noopener">企业和家庭的信心恢复缓慢</a>，导致他们增加投资和支出的意愿有限。 BCA Research 首席新兴市场策略师阿瑟·布达吉安 (Arthur Budaghyan) 表示，这样的环境使得温和的刺激措施基本上无效。</p><p> “中国政府必须采取一些非常大的行动来应对通货紧缩，”他说。 “我认为他们做得还不够。”</p><p class="articleTagLine"> ——北京的 Grace Zhu 和晓晓对本文做出了贡献。</p><p>写信给谢一凡<a href="mailto:stella.xie@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">stella.xie@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Wed, 09 Aug 2023 09:21:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/china-slips-into-deflation-in-warning-sign-for-world-economy-bbefb179</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/china-slips-into-deflation-in-warning-sign-for-world-economy-bbefb179<author><![CDATA[Stella Yifan Xie]]></author><category>原生金属</category><category>黑色金属</category><category>基本材料/资源</category><category>经济表现/指标</category><category>通货膨胀数字/价格指数</category><category>货币政策</category><category>利率</category><category>经济新闻</category><category>消费者价格指数</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>呼吸道疾病</category><category>健康</category><category>医疗条件</category><category>疫情/流行病</category><category>新型冠状病毒</category><category>传染性疾病</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>经济表现</category><category>指标</category><category>通货膨胀数字</category><category>价格指数</category><category>货币政策</category><category>利率</category><category>经济新闻</category><category>消费者价格指数</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>呼吸道疾病</category><category>健康</category><category>医疗条件</category><category>爆发</category><category>流行病</category><category>新型冠状病毒</category><category>传染性疾病</category><category>原生金属</category><category>黑色金属</category><category>基础材料</category><category>资源</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[U.S. to Ban Some Investments in China]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>拜登总统计划签署一项新的行政命令，该命令还将要求美国私募股权和风险投资公司披露在中国的某些投资<!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001120961"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-832248?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">拜登政府去年限制向中国出口先进半导体和芯片制造设备。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：乔纳森·恩斯特/路透社</p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001120961"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/andrew-duehren" itemprop="url" rel="author">安德鲁·杜伦</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 8 月 9 日上午 12:56 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-to-ban-some-investments-in-china-71f519d6"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p>根据拜登政府周三发布的一项行政命令，美国将禁止对一些中国科技公司进行私募股权和风险投资，这将加大华盛顿阻止北京为其军队开发尖端技术的力度。</p><p>该行政命令预计将涵盖半导体、量子计算和人工智能三个技术领域的直接投资。它将禁止对这些技术的某些形式进行投资，同时要求在中国做生意的美国人向美国政府通报更广泛地对这三个高科技领域的投资。</p><p>据知情人士透露，违反这些规定的投资者可能会面临罚款，并被迫剥离所持股份。在执行新规则之前，预计拜登政府将接受有关这些规则的反馈。知情人士称，预计它们将适用于未来的交易，但不会涵盖中国股票和债券的投资组合。</p><p>从技术上讲，这些规则预计也适用于对俄罗斯等其他对手的投资，但预计它们实际上只会影响美国对中国的投资。</p><p>财政部发言人拒绝置评。</p><p>这项行政命令是两党日益担心的产物，担心美国的技术和专门知识可能会无意中帮助北京开发可在军事冲突中用来对抗美国的武器。拜登政府去年限制向中国出口先进半导体和芯片制造设备，美国也加强了对中国对美国科技公司投资的审查。</p><p>尽管拜登政府官员将这些举措视为保护美国国家安全的有针对性的举措，但北京官员表示，这些举措的目的是限制中国的经济增长和发展。中国领导人习近平去年向拜登总统抱怨半导体出口管制。今年早些时候， <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/beijing-bans-micron-as-supplier-to-big-chinese-firms-citing-national-security-5f326b90?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">中国禁止国内大公司</a>从美国最大的存储芯片制造商<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/MU" class="">美光科技</a>购买技术，此举被广泛解读为对美国出口限制<span class="company-name-type">的</span>报复。</p><p>新的投资限制可能会导致两个超级大国之间试图解冻的外交关系重新冻结。</p><div class="media-object scope-web
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4>分享你的意见</h4><p><em>美国对中国企业投资的最佳限制是什么？加入下面的对话。</em></p></div></div><p>近年来，随着地缘政治竞争加剧，美国对华投资曾帮助推动中国经济发展，但投资有所放缓。据荣鼎集团称，去年美国对华直接投资跌至 20 年来最低点 82 亿美元，该公司还表示，去年美国风险资本投资跌至 10 年来最低点 13 亿美元。</p><p>目前尚不清楚其中有多少资金流向了目标行业。乔治城大学研究人员的一份报告发现，2015年至2021年间，美国投资者参与了中国人工智能公司的401笔交易，同期纯美国投资者的投资额达74.5亿美元。</p><p>据知情人士透露，在起草行政命令时，拜登政府官员在如何区分主要构成国家安全风险的人工智能形式和广泛用于日常商业目的的其他形式人工智能方面遇到了困难。</p><p>甚至在新的资本管制措施发布之前，它就已经开始重塑美国投资者的行为。经过华盛顿的持续审查，风险投资基金红杉资本今年早些时候剥离了其中国业务。据知情人士透露，其他公司在等待新规定期间已经放缓或暂停了在中国的交易。</p><p>华盛顿的行业组织试图缩小拜登政府花了一年多时间制定的规则。</p><p>其他限制美国对华投资的提议范围更广。去年，一个由两党议员组成的小组呼吁成立一个跨部门小组，负责筛选更广泛技术领域的投资。今年，两位立法者在参议院通过的年度国防政策法案修正案中恢复了该计划的要素。他们的立法将要求披露投资，而不是禁止，并且可能不会成为法律。</p><p>威斯康星州共和党众议员迈克·加拉格尔 (Mike Gallagher) 和众议院中国事务委员会呼吁对流入中国的美国证券投资进行同样的限制。在最近的一封信中，该委员会批评<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/BLK" class="company-name">贝莱德</a>和顶级股市指数编制机构摩根士丹利资本国际(MSCI)为对中国公司的投资提供便利，美国政府指责这些公司支持中国军事并侵犯人权。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=36C897CD-0391-4CD6-A2F4-AAB54C8FB90E&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fu-s-to-ban-some-investments-in-china-71f519d6&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption">美国在20世纪50年代发明了太阳能电池板。但在全球市场上主导该技术的却是中国。 《华尔街日报》审视了该行业的权力动态，以及美国是否能够重新夺回其先锋地位。图片插图：Amogh Alva Vaz<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div><p>据知情人士透露，在拜登政府内部，财政部和商务部的官员已成功寻求限制行政命令的范围。财政部官员历来的任务是倡导美国对中国进行更多投资而不是限制投资，他们担心制定一套可能难以执行的规则。他们还希望保留美国的大量投资，并推动将规则针对对国家安全特别敏感的技术。</p><p>美国还一直在敦促其欧洲和亚洲盟友采取类似措施限制对中国的投资，希望阻止企业简单地通过伦敦或东京等地转移资金。经过美国的游说，七国集团在春季一致认为，资本管制“对于补充现有的针对出口和入境投资的定向控制工具可能很重要”。欧盟委员会建议这个由 27 个成员国组成的欧盟对海外投资采取限制措施。</p><p>写信给安德鲁·杜伦 (Andrew Duehren)，邮箱为<a href="mailto:andrew.duehren@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">andrew.duehren@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Wed, 09 Aug 2023 04:56:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/us-to-ban-some-investments-in-china-71f519d6</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/us-to-ban-some-investments-in-china-71f519d6<author><![CDATA[Andrew Duehren]]></author><category>信托/基金/金融工具</category><category>私人产权</category><category>另类投资</category><category>金融服务</category><category>金融科技</category><category>投资/证券</category><category>技术</category><category>风险投资</category><category>法规/政府政策</category><category>所有权变更</category><category>收购/合并/持股</category><category>研究和发展</category><category>收购/合并</category><category>企业行动</category><category>企业/行业新闻</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>规定</category><category>政府政策</category><category>所有权变更</category><category>收购</category><category>合并</category><category>持股</category><category>研究</category><category>发展</category><category>企业行动</category><category>公司的</category><category>行业新闻</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>政治</category><category>国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>信托</category><category>资金</category><category>金融工具</category><category>私人产权</category><category>另类投资</category><category>金融服务</category><category>金融科技</category><category>投资</category><category>证券</category><category>技术</category><category>风险投资</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[One of America’s Favorite Generals Leads the Niger Coup]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>双桅船。穆萨·萨拉乌·巴尔穆将军长期以来一直被华盛顿视为打击伊斯兰极端主义的合作伙伴，现已成为美国与军政府之间的主要外交渠道<figure><img src="https://images.wsj.net/im-832012/?width=1278&amp;size=1" alt="双桅船。美国和军政府之间的主要外交渠道穆萨·萨劳·巴尔穆将军（左）于 6 月会见了美国陆军特种作战司令部司令，讨论反恐政策。" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>双桅船。美国和军政府之间的主要外交渠道穆萨·萨劳·巴尔穆将军（左）于 6 月会见了美国陆军特种作战司令部司令，讨论反恐政策。参谋军士。艾米·杨格/美国空军<span>参谋中士。艾米·杨格/美国空军</span></figcaption></figure><!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001119404"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001119404"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/michael-m-phillips" itemprop="url" rel="author">迈克尔·M·菲利普斯</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">更新于 2023 年 8 月 9 日上午 12:46（美国东部时间） </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/niger-coup-us-trained-general-65b5ecd6"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bigtophero
"></div><p>内罗毕——上个月，当<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/niger-coup-president-us-fumble-russia-africa-86cf1454-33d18bc?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">一群高级军官在尼日尔夺取政权时，美国军事指挥官</a>感到沮丧。尼日尔是美国在西非打击伊斯兰武装分子的主要盟友。</p><p>最刺痛的也许是电视上播放的一个人的画面，准将。穆萨·萨拉乌·巴尔穆将军是政变策划者之一。</p><p>巴尔穆是美国军方近30年来一直追求的对象。他是美国派往华盛顿特区著名的国防大学的人。他是一个邀请美国军官到他家吃饭的人。他负责精锐部队，这对于阻止基地组织和伊斯兰国武装分子在西非的泛滥至关重要。</p><p> “布里格。几个月前，一位美国国防官员表示，“巴尔穆将军就是那个人。”</p><p>他可能仍然是。</p><p>尼日尔政变后的两周内，巴尔穆已成为美国与军政府之间的主要外交渠道。美国官员和外交官的手机里有他的号码，他们认为他是他们恢复民主和防止一场混乱的地区战争的最佳机会，这场战争将使世界上最贫穷的地区之一陷入更深的危机。</p><p>巴尔穆周一在尼日尔首都尼亚美与美国代理副国务卿维多利亚·纽兰进行了两个小时的会谈。迄今为止的谈判结果令人沮丧。但纽兰知道巴尔穆长期以来对美国的好感，敦促他促成一项协议，使尼日尔及其长期西方盟友能够重新打击基地组织、伊斯兰国和博科圣地武装分子，并阻止该国成为<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/niger-coup-us-russia-africa-86cf1454?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">另一个非洲前哨基地。俄罗斯</a>及其准军事瓦格纳集团。</p><p>退役空军少将马克·希克斯 (Mark Hicks) 表示：“我们很多喜欢他的人都希望他能帮助引导这件事实现软着陆。”他曾于 2017 年至 2019 年领导美国驻非洲特种作战部队，并认为巴尔穆是一位亲密的私人朋友。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-831994?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">数千人在尼亚美法国大使馆前举行集会，支持推翻民选总统穆罕默德·巴祖姆的军事政变。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：法新社/盖蒂图片社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>但事实仍然是，没有比巴尔穆更能生动地象征美国在西非反恐行动的希望破灭了。在双方利益出现分歧之前，巴尔穆对美国战略至关重要。</p><h3>萨赫勒战略</h3><p>萨赫勒地区是撒哈拉以南的一个半干旱地区，近年来，圣战分子在那里造成了数千人死亡，使其成为二十多年来与伊斯兰极端分子作战的世界上最大的战场之一。美军做法的核心是派遣美国突击队训练当地特种部队来领导战役。巴尔穆的部队是尼日尔最精锐的战斗力量， <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-builds-new-firewall-to-stop-spread-of-militant-islamists-11670771719?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">他是这一举措的关键人物</a>。</p><p>希克斯说：“如果政变造成尼日尔失去一个据点，那么美国在该地区的战略利益将受到挫败。”尼日尔“是圣战骚乱海洋中的稳定之岛”。</p><p>过去两年， <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/in-africa-u-s-trained-militaries-are-ousting-civilian-governments-in-coups-11649505601?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">马里、布基纳法索和现在的尼日尔发生的军事政变</a>让人怀疑美国能否帮助萨赫勒国家抵御伊斯兰叛乱，同时阻止莫斯科利用不稳定局势。</p><p>以地区强国尼日利亚为首的邻国威胁要向尼日尔派遣军队，营救仍被关押在尼亚美的被驱逐的总统穆罕默德·巴祖姆，并让他重新掌权。布基纳法索和马里的军政府已承诺支持尼日尔的新军事政权，他们雇佣了与克里姆林宫有联系的瓦格纳雇佣兵，试图压制自己的武装威胁，但失败了。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><img width="600" height="882" src="https://s.wsj.net/public/resources/images/0ba284ff-8568-411e-8e57-25ff84d48d04-fallback_app.jpg" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p>这场对峙增加了萨赫勒地区可能被一场新的地区战争和现有的​​伊斯兰叛乱所吞噬的可能性。</p><p>在军政府提拔他为国防参谋长之前，巴尔穆一直负责指挥尼日尔特种部队。他的部下与美国绿色贝雷帽并肩作战，直到 7 月 26 日反对巴祖姆的起义，此时距他上任仅两年多。和巴尔穆一样，巴祖姆也是美国的宠儿，拜登政府立即要求他重新掌权。</p><p>美国已花费约 5 亿美元建设尼日尔国防军，其中包括耗资 1.1 亿美元在阿加德兹镇建造的美国无人机基地，并在该国驻扎了约 1,100 名美军。美国突击队与巴尔穆的部队在瓦拉姆镇和迪法镇共享前哨基地，在那里他们与当地的基地组织和伊斯兰国势力作战，而迪法的战斗行动重点是在乍得湖周围发动袭击的博科圣地武装分子。</p><p>军事叛乱发生后，美国暂停了对尼日尔军队的训练，并削减了对尼日尔的一些其他军事援助。如果国务院正式宣布起义为政变，美国法律将要求进一步减少军事援助。美国誓言将继续向尼日尔提供粮食和其他人道主义援助。</p><p>巴尔穆很清楚，政变可能会让他失去关键的战斗支持——不再有联合训练、美国绿色贝雷帽的战术建议或发送实时监视的美国无人机。</p><p> “如果这是为我们的主权付出的代价，那就顺其自然吧，”政变几天后，巴尔穆在给《华尔街日报》的信中写道。他没有回答本文的进一步问题。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-831999?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">尼日尔瓦拉姆附近的萨赫勒地区，这片大陆的大片地区曾被伊斯兰极端分子利用。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：迈克尔·M·菲利普斯/《华尔街日报》 </p></figcaption></figure></div><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-831997?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">巴尔穆的手下与美国绿色贝雷帽部队密切合作，直到七月起义。上图为 11 月，尼日尔突击队员在瓦拉姆与美军一起训练。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：迈克尔·M·菲利普斯/《华尔街日报》</p></figcaption></figure></div><h3> “极其坦率”</h3><p>美国官员正试图弄清楚巴尔穆是否认为他和他的将军们是稳定尼日尔的最佳希望，或者他是否愿意帮助谈判恢复文官统治。</p><p>副国务卿努兰将本周在尼亚美与巴尔穆的会谈描述为“极其坦率，有时相当困难”——用外交家的话来说，会谈激烈但不成功。</p><p>努兰在会后告诉记者：“他们对于如何推进的想法非常坚定，这不符合尼日尔宪法。”在与巴尔穆的会谈中，纽兰利用了他与美国特种部队的长期联系，提醒他，除非恢复民主秩序，否则尼日尔可能会失去美国的军事援助。</p><p>其他西非安全官员表示，华盛顿能否成功让巴尔穆站在他们一边将至关重要。该地区的一名高级军官表示，美国的外交努力仍然是“不流血”结果的最佳希望。</p><p> “美国将不得不做出选择——留在尼日尔还是把这个地方留给瓦格纳，”这位官员说。</p><p>从12岁起，军队就一直是巴尔穆生活的中心，当时他在邻居的启发下离开尼日尔前往科特迪瓦的军校。然后他进入喀麦隆的一所军事学院。</p><p> 1960 年尼日尔从法国独立后，巴尔穆的父亲担任公务员，他不鼓励儿子参军，而是希望他继续学业。</p><p>但年轻的巴尔穆决心已定，并于 1989 年参军。美国军方很早就将他视为后起之秀，并采取措施将他拉入美国轨道。</p><p> 1994年，他在圣安东尼奥拉克兰空军基地参加了英语课程。现在，他的英语、法语和豪萨语（一种从尼日利亚到苏丹都使用的语言）都非常流利，以至于一名美国官员表示，在国际会议上，这位将军有时似乎忘记了自己在说哪一种语言。</p><p>美国政府派巴尔穆在当时的佐治亚州本宁堡参加一系列课程，训练他领导步兵攻击和从飞机上跳伞。除其他互动外，他还参加了联合特种作战大学的课程，该大学毗邻坦帕的美国特种作战司令部总部。</p><p>巴尔穆回忆说，早在20世纪90年代，尼日尔就认识到了伊斯兰极端分子的威胁，当时这些极端分子正从阿尔及利亚涌出，前往尼日尔寻求庇护。</p><p> “虽然其他一些国家否认他们存在恐怖主义问题，并且一些国家仍在试图与恐怖分子进行谈判，但在尼日尔，我们决定不会让这种情况发生，”巴尔穆在 11 月接受采访时表示。</p><p> 2004年，巴尔穆担任尼日尔第一个特种部队连的指挥，由美国突击队训练。三年后，他离开了这个职位，搬到了华盛顿特区，并在波托马克河和阿纳科斯蒂亚河交汇处的国防大学获得了战略安全研究硕士学位。</p><p>回到西非，隶属于基地组织和后来的伊斯兰国的激进组织开始通过残暴和灵活地利用现有村庄的不满情绪（例如牧民和农民之间的土地权利纠纷）取得进展。在某些情况下，基地组织战士通过与当地妇女结婚来巩固自己的地位。</p><p>首先，武装分子涌入马里，到 2017 年，他们又在布基纳法索和尼日尔发动袭击。那一年，四名美国士兵和五名尼日尔士兵在“伊斯兰国”组织在通戈通戈村的伏击中丧生。美国绿色贝雷帽小组主要为巴尔穆的部队提供远离危险的阵地的建议。</p><p>美国认为尼日尔的特种部队是西非最好的特种部队之一，在马里和布基纳法索的军事领导人驱逐西方军队后， <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-builds-new-firewall-to-stop-spread-of-militant-islamists-11670771719?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">华盛顿将尼日尔视为对抗暴力极端分子的防火线</a>。尼日尔没有表现出雇用瓦格纳雇佣兵的意愿，这让美国尤其松了一口气。</p><p> “从一开始，我们就与美国建立了牢固的伙伴关系，”巴尔穆在 11 月表示。 “它们对我们来说非常重要。”就在尼日尔军队封锁巴祖姆总统官邸不到六周前，美国军方发布了一张巴尔穆在尼日尔和尼日尔两国共享的尼亚美空军基地微笑拥抱美国陆军特种作战司令部司令乔纳森·布拉加中将的照片。美国军队。据随附的推文称，这次访问的目的是讨论反恐政策和策略。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-831995?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">六月，巴尔穆在尼亚美开会前拥抱了一名身份不明的美国军人。美国军方在推特上发布了这张照片。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：参谋军士。艾米·杨格/美国空军</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>有时，这些职业联盟会融入个人友谊。巴尔穆曾带一只煮熟的山羊到尼亚美的一个安全屋，与时任美国特种作战司令希克斯和美国大使馆人员共进晚餐。</p><p>尼日尔前殖民国家法国的情况并非如此，在与美国同行的会晤中，巴尔穆自由地表达了反法情绪。据一名美国官员称，2021 年，他在尼亚美的家中举办了一场除夕派对，邀请了美国和英国官员，但没有邀请法国官员。该官员表示，巴尔穆对法国在没有咨询尼日尔指挥官的情况下自行针对激进组织采取行动的做法感到不满。</p><p>尽管美国和军政府之间的谈判起步缓慢，但巴尔穆的美国朋友希望他有政治回旋余地和个人意愿游说达成解决方案，使尼日尔站在华盛顿一边。</p><p>然而，纽兰在离开本周与巴尔穆的会面时，连进一步会谈的承诺都没有。军政府拒绝允许她探访被监禁的当选总统巴祖姆或奥马尔·奇亚尼将军，后者在几个小时内就从巴祖姆的总统卫队指挥官变成了巴祖姆自封的继任者。</p><p> “因此，我们只能依靠巴尔穆先生来再次明确利害攸关的问题，”纽兰说。</p><p>写信给迈克尔·菲利普斯 (Michael M. Phillips)： <a href="mailto:Michael.Phillips@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">Michael.Phillips@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Wed, 09 Aug 2023 04:46:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/niger-coup-us-trained-general-65b5ecd6</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/niger-coup-us-trained-general-65b5ecd6<author><![CDATA[Michael M. Phillips]]></author><category>领导者</category><category>华尔街日报</category><category>gfx-contrib</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>国家/公共安全</category><category>叛乱</category><category>犯罪/法律诉讼</category><category>武装部队</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>风险新闻</category><category>恐怖主义</category><category>军事行动</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>穆罕默德·巴祖姆</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>国家的</category><category>公安</category><category>叛乱</category><category>犯罪</category><category>合法举动</category><category>武装部队</category><category>政治</category><category>国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>风险新闻</category><category>恐怖主义</category><category>军事行动</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Returning Ukrainian Refugees Say There’s No Place Like Home]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>回返者表示，家乡的熟悉感压倒了战区生活的不安全感<figure><img src="https://images.wsj.net/im-831560/?width=1278&amp;size=1" alt="俄罗斯入侵后，亚里娜·雅霍德金娜 (Yaryna Yahodkina) 带着孩子们前往波兰，但现在他们已返回乌克兰。" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>俄罗斯入侵后，亚里娜·雅霍德金娜 (Yaryna Yahodkina) 带着孩子们前往波兰，但现在他们已返回乌克兰。 Serhii Korovayny for The Wall Street Journal <span>Serhii Korovayny for The Wall Street Journal</span> </figcaption></figure><!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001118142"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001118142"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline">作者： <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/anastasiia-malenko" itemprop="url" rel="author">阿纳斯塔西娅·马伦科</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">更新于 2023 年 8 月 9 日上午 12:11（东部时间） </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/returning-ukrainian-refugees-say-theres-no-place-like-home-56cd2969"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bigtophero
"></div><p>去年，当俄罗斯军队逼近她的家乡时，亚里娜·雅霍德金娜 (Yaryna Yahodkina) 带着两个年幼的孩子， <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/ukraine-russia-war-immigration-refugees-11669241333?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">与数百万乌克兰人一起</a>逃往国外，留下她的丈夫在战斗。</p><p>现在，一家人又回到了乌克兰，在宵禁下生活在距离巴赫穆特市以西仅 60 英里的地方，巴赫穆特市是迄今为止<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/brutal-battle-for-bakhmut-leaves-russia-with-an-uncertain-victory-29b56da7?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">战争中最长、最血腥的战斗</a>发生地。</p><p> “导弹可以飞到任何城镇，所以我们只希望它不会是我们的，”雅霍德金纳说。</p><p>随着与俄罗斯的冲突持续下去，这位 29 岁的年轻人面临着两难境地：在异国他乡是安全的，还是在家乡熟悉的，即使它已经成为战区。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-831569?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">雅霍德金娜 (Yahodkina) 与丈夫和孩子在乌克兰东部的多布罗皮利亚 (Dobropillia)。 “我和我的人民一样完全支持和理解我，”她说。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：《华尔街日报》的 Serhii Korovayny</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> 2022 年 2 月全面战争爆发时，约有 800 万人逃离乌克兰，许多人希望这次逃离的时间不会太长。据联合国称，随着冲突进入第二年， <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/ukraine-gains-territory-as-russia-grapples-with-wagners-aborted-mutiny-67f67b19?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">乌克兰反击</a>俄罗斯的进攻，约有 620 万乌克兰人仍留在国外，这一数字表明约有 180 万乌克兰人<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/ukrainian-refugees-are-heading-home-in-droves-11652695585?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">已返回祖国</a>。</p><p>联合国国际移民组织2023年5月至6月进行的一项调查估计，约有100万在国外的乌克兰人返回原籍地访问或停留。另有 353,000 人从国外返回，但仍在乌克兰境内流离失所。</p><p>受访的海归人员绝大多数将家庭团聚作为原因。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><img width="600" height="894" src="https://s.wsj.net/public/resources/images/6d46f641-8f07-47f4-a32b-4a87e9141187-fallback_app.jpg" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p>他们的到来提振了乌克兰的经济和士气，对该国的长期前景至关重要。</p><p>乌克兰总统泽伦斯基表示：“如果人们不回来，我们就不会有强劲的经济。”</p>六月说。<p></p><p>经济部表示，预计每10万居住在海外的乌克兰人，乌克兰的国内生产总值就会下降0.5%。乌克兰经济部数据显示，2022 年乌克兰 GDP 萎缩三分之一。</p><p> The pull of family, financial security and social and job satisfaction is winning out over safety, the main factor that pushed Ukrainians to leave, say returnees and those working with them.</p><p> At the outbreak of the conflict, Yahodkina went to Poland, where she and her children stayed with a host family in a small village. Without a car or driver&#39;s license, she couldn&#39;t travel to find a job.</p><p> After her husband was injured in battle, she returned to Dobropillia, a town with a prewar population of some 28,000 inhabitants, in eastern Ukraine to take care of him in May. There is limited water supply, early curfew and “constant missiles overhead,” she said, but “I am among my people who fully support and understand me.” </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-831562?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Dobropillia had a prewar population of some 28,000 inhabitants and now has a limited water supply and an early curfew.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Serhii Korovayny for The Wall Street Journal</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> The current wave of Ukrainians going home mostly consists of those who haven&#39;t managed to secure stable employment and housing abroad, said Kseniia Gashchak, who works with Ukrainian refugees in Berlin. There are also those with aging family members or males who aren&#39;t permitted to leave the country.</p><p> Olga Dyvynska, 36, wanted to be closer to her husband serving in Ukraine&#39;s armed forces, help her mother take care of her paralyzed grandmother and send her daughter to a Ukrainian school.</p><p> She left Poland in May as Kyiv suffered <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/russia-launches-largest-drone-attack-on-kyiv-since-start-of-war-a68c2daa?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">a barrage of Russian airstrikes</a> and remembers asking herself: “Why did I do this?”</p><p> For her, it was her 5-year-old daughter&#39;s joy when she had returned to kindergarten during brief visits to Ukraine. “她会跑到那里。 I couldn&#39;t get her to come home despite air-raid alerts,” Dyvynska said. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-831567?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Olga Dyvynska and her daughter returned to Ukraine from Poland in May.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Emanuele Satolli for The Wall Street Journal</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> Attractive job opportunities are also central to the Ministry of Economy&#39;s strategy to rebuild its workforce, even as the war has caused openings to dwindle. In the first half of this year, Ukraine had 172,000 vacancies, down from nearly 235,000 registered during the same period in 2022 by the State Employment Service.</p><p> Government programs provide grants for businesses to stimulate job creation in sectors ranging from IT startups to winemaking.</p><p> These are designed to achieve the broader ministry goal of attracting 4.5 million people to the labor market in the next 10 years. “Recovery of the labor market is not a consequence of the victory, it is a path to victory,” Deputy Minister of Economy Tetyana Berezhna said in July.</p><p> Life in Ukraine is also more affordable than living overseas, returnees say, especially for the many who remained on a Ukrainian salary while working remotely.</p><p> “A thing that calmed me down after I returned to Ukraine is that I can provide a life for myself here,” said Sofiia Zubova, 22, who hails from the central city of Kryviy Rih where Russia launched a <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/russia-kills-six-more-civilians-as-ukrainians-struggle-to-resume-routine-bca89603?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">deadly missile strike on residential buildings</a> in late July.</p><p> Working for a Ukrainian company while in the Czech Republic didn&#39;t allow Zubova to earn enough to live independently from her host family. “我感觉自己就像一个有了更多零用钱的青少年，”她说。 Now, when she is scared by explosions, she sleeps in the hallway and said the fear is less acute at home.</p><p> Some Ukrainians began returning in late spring last year, before Russia&#39;s winter campaign against the country&#39;s power grid took hold and <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/ukraines-power-shortages-force-millions-of-refugees-into-lengthier-exile-11669800976?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">paused re-entry plans</a> .</p><p> As the conflict <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/ukraine-adopts-slow-approach-to-counteroffensive-our-problem-everywhere-is-the-sky-a2e51d7a?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">has stabilized along the front lines</a> , more have headed home leaving life as refugees behind. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-831570?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Sofiia Kaluhina went to the Netherlands as a refugee but said the sense of safety didn&#39;t compensate for the life she missed in Ukraine.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Emanuele Satolli for The Wall Street Journal</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> Sofiia Kaluhina, 22, had been living in the Netherlands in old office space converted into free housing for Ukrainian refugees.</p><p> “We had to put wallpaper over the glass walls but the gaps would remain, and you could hear everything,” said Kaluhina, a freelance artist.</p><p> She found companions among curators and painters but missed running into friends in her favorite bar in the Ukrainian capital. “基辅有一些地方让我可以去并且有宾至如归的感觉。在荷兰，我找不到类似的东西，”她说。 The sense of safety didn&#39;t compensate for the life she missed in Ukraine, Kaluhina said.</p><p> For some, returning home has involved adjustment. 35 岁的奥莱娜·比奇科娃 (Olena Bychkova) 面临着财务挑战，因为她没有作为难民获得的护栏，例如东道主的免费住房和政府的财政支持。她还失去了在国外租赁乌克兰公寓的收入。 Bychkova has taken a job as a fundraiser for a Ukraine-based nongovernmental organization, which she said makes better use of her university education than the position at a gas station cafe in Lithuania where she worked after fleeing the war.</p><p> “I had to start everything from scratch. I did not know the language in the country at all, it was difficult,” said Bychkova.</p><p> Her 6-year-old daughter, Janelle, also seems more at ease in Ukraine. “She sings when she is happy,” Bychkova said, “And here she sings every day.”</p><p> Write to Anastasiia Malenko at <a href="mailto:anastasiia.malenko@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">anastasiia.malenko@wsj.com</a> </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-831572?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Olena Bychkova says her daughter Janelle seems more at ease in Ukraine.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Emanuele Satolli for The Wall Street Journal</p></figcaption></figure></div></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Wed, 09 Aug 2023 04:11:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/returning-ukrainian-refugees-say-theres-no-place-like-home-56cd2969</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/returning-ukrainian-refugees-say-theres-no-place-like-home-56cd2969<author><![CDATA[Anastasiia Malenko]]></author><category> gfx-contrib</category><category>乌克兰</category><category>wsjworld</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>Charities/Volunteering</category><category>国家/公共安全</category><category>社会/社区</category><category>Human Migration</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>风险新闻</category><category>军事行动</category><category>乌克兰</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>charities</category><category> volunteering</category><category> national</category><category>公安</category><category>社会</category><category>社区</category><category>human migration</category><category>政治</category><category>国际关系</category><category>风险新闻</category><category>军事行动</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Earth Just Had Its Hottest Month Ever. How Six Cities Are Coping.]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> As the planet bakes, heat waves affect hundreds of millions across the Northern Hemisphere <figure><img src="https://images.wsj.net/im-831315/?width=1278&amp;size=1" alt="Phoenix experienced the hottest-ever month for a U.S. city in July, with a record 16-day stretch when the temperatures didn’t go below 90 degrees at night." referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption> Phoenix experienced the hottest-ever month for a US city in July, with a record 16-day stretch when the temperatures didn&#39;t go below 90 degrees at night. Matt York/Associated Press <span>Matt York/Associated Press</span> </figcaption></figure><!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001117026"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001117026"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/aylin-woodward" itemprop="url" rel="author">Aylin Woodward</a></span> , <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/carl-churchill" itemprop="url" rel="author">Carl Churchill</a></span> and <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/erin-ailworth" itemprop="url" rel="author">Erin Ailworth</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> Updated Aug. 8, 2023 4:40 pm ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/july-2023-hottest-month-record-climate-change-5e5b3097"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bigtophero
"></div><p> July was Earth&#39;s hottest month on record, surpassing the global monthly average temperature record set in July 2019, according to <a href="https://urldefense.com/v3/__https://climate.copernicus.eu/july-2023-sees-multiple-global-temperature-records-broken?utm_source=press&amp;utm_medium=referral&amp;utm_campaign=CBjuly23__;!!F0Stn7g!AXLdNbU2IY7PVik0Ny92LEUoMSpQWj0RV1VfEFWVvLWYL9QaVTeYQJvLJXYu4oYlNAYXAWXU1ibmG9X6NdMZg-iwCBtc$" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noopener">data</a> from the Copernicus Climate Change Service, a European Union-funded scientific agency. The <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/extreme-heat-waves-across-the-world-photos-7cc1544d?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">heat blanketed</a> parts of North America, Asia and Europe as wildfires blazed in Greece and Canada, hitting economies. Water shortages and high humidity affected parts of the Middle East. Residents in China contended with both extreme flooding and a heat wave as the country set a new national temperature record. All this came on the heels of the <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/june-hottest-on-record-heat-b222c05c?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">world&#39;s hottest June</a> on record. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><img width="600" height="660" src="https://s.wsj.net/public/resources/images/5700be35-99b9-42cf-938b-84ccedf084a3-fallback_app.jpg" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p> Parts of the US experienced record-breaking heat as well. July <a href="https://www.ncei.noaa.gov/news/national-climate-202307" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noopener">was the warmest month on record</a> for states such as Arizona and New Mexico, the National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration said Tuesday. Agency data also show that <a href="https://www.ncdc.noaa.gov/cdo-web/datatools/records" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noopener">more than 3,000 daily temperature records</a> were broken or tied across the country last month. Even cities in typically colder areas such as Alaska experienced unprecedentedly high temperatures. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><img width="600" height="800" src="https://s.wsj.net/public/resources/images/919b11ea-79c3-41ee-b02c-a239d84227c3-fallback_app.jpg" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p> July is always, on average, the hottest month of the year annually, but these temperature records represent merely the newest iteration of what has become a notable pattern over the past decade. The world <a href="https://public.wmo.int/en/media/press-release/past-eight-years-confirmed-be-eight-warmest-record" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noopener">experienced the eight warmest years</a> on record globally from 2015 through 2022, the World Meteorological Organization reported earlier this year. The global ocean, too, is part of this pattern: Roughly, the last 10 years were among <a href="https://climate.nasa.gov/vital-signs/ocean-warming/" target="_blank" class="icon none">the ocean&#39;s warmest</a> since at least the 1800s, and the Copernicus agency, a division of the European Centre for Medium-Range Weather Forecasts, found that global sea-surface temperatures <a href="https://urldefense.com/v3/__https://climate.copernicus.eu/global-sea-surface-temperature-reaches-record-high?utm_source=press&amp;utm_medium=referral&amp;utm_campaign=CBjuly23__;!!F0Stn7g!AXLdNbU2IY7PVik0Ny92LEUoMSpQWj0RV1VfEFWVvLWYL9QaVTeYQJvLJXYu4oYlNAYXAWXU1ibmG9X6NdMZg31wZO8C$" target="_blank" class="icon none">remained at record-high levels</a> last month.</p><p> “What seems unprecedented this year now will just be normal a few years from now,” said Tapio Schneider, a California Institute of Technology climate scientist.</p><p> Heat waves have become quotidian problems in the summer. And this year, much as in 2016, a powerful <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/ocean-warming-el-nino-noaa-ec2f124?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">El Niño weather pattern</a> developing in the Pacific has liberated heat from the ocean depths, redistributing it into the atmosphere, amplifying the effects of climate change driven by fossil-fuel emissions.</p><p> The Wall Street Journal looked at some of the cities around the world that are among those that have been affected in different ways by rising temperatures.</p><h3> PHOENIX, ARIZ. </h3><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bleed
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/projects/narrator/3ee552ce-fa50-4cd0-ab70-f7a07f283860.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><p> Excessive heat is the No. 1 weather-related killer in the US, <a href="https://www.weather.gov/phi/heat#:~:text=A%20look%20at%20weather%20fatality,the%20effects%20of%20excessive%20heat." target="_blank" class="icon none">according to the National Weather Service</a> . High temperatures <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/high-temperatures-affect-human-body-11658262757" target="_blank" class="icon none">can be a risk to anyone</a> , public-health experts say. But those in vulnerable groups are especially at risk, including the elderly, infants and people with pre-existing conditions, such as cardiovascular or pulmonary diseases. A study published recently found the <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/extreme-heat-air-quality-heart-attack-risk-d3790927?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">risk for heart attack doubles</a> during heat waves that last several days and overlap with periods of poor air quality.</p><p> Phoenix residents endured <a href="https://twitter.com/NWSPhoenix/status/1686167833162760197" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noopener">a record stretch of it in July</a> , when daytime temperatures hit 110 degrees or above for 31 consecutive days—the hottest month ever in a US city. Phoenix also clocked a record 16-day stretch when the temperatures didn&#39;t go below 90 degrees at night. That nighttime heat has been responsible for a growing number of heat-related deaths. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><img width="600" height="650" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-831645?width=600" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p> So far this year, Maricopa County, where Phoenix is located, has recorded 39 heat-associated deaths and is investigating another 312, according to the most recent weekly report from the public-health department.</p><p> There were a record 425 heat-associated deaths in 2022, a 25% increase from the previous year, according to Maricopa&#39;s public-health department.</p><p> Sonia Singh, spokeswoman for Maricopa&#39;s public-health department, said it is hard to pinpoint exactly what caused the jump because so many factors can play into a heat-associated death, including a person&#39;s housing situation, substance use and access to healthcare.</p><p> “This is a lot more than we&#39;re used to,” Singh said of the recent and unusually long spate of extreme temperatures. “Everybody needs to have a plan for where they can go to escape the heat.” </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><img width="600" height="904" src="https://s.wsj.net/public/resources/images/8e721efe-2083-4856-81c8-b7936e38e011-fallback_app.jpg" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p> Even places such as Arizona that routinely experience extreme heat have struggled to get people to pay attention to the risks, according to Kristie Ebi, a professor who researches health risks in a changing climate at the University of Washington&#39;s Center for Health and the Global Environment.</p><p> “You talk with people who say, &#39;Oh, I can remember heat waves from a couple of years ago…was fine.&#39;” she said “Today&#39;s hot isn&#39;t hot five years ago—it is a different hot and that is not easy to communicate.”</p><div class="media-object scope-web,mobileapps
          wrap
"></div><p> Heat-related deaths in the US have been on the rise for the last five years, data from the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention show. The agency, on average, has recorded some 1,200 deaths each year from 2018 to 2022. The agency said that better reporting might be a factor, particularly as people have become more aware of how heat can contribute to death cases. In contrast, heart disease, <a href="https://www.cdc.gov/nchs/fastats/leading-causes-of-death.htm" target="_blank" class="icon none">the leading cause of death in the US</a> , sees hundreds of thousands of deaths recorded each year by the agency.</p><p> Ebi said the number of heat deaths is “massively underestimated,” and that the real number is closer to 10,000 when factoring in people who died of things such as heart issues brought on by heat.</p><p> “Heat is underlying so many people going into emergency room departments and dying during heat waves,” she said. “But death certificates aren&#39;t recording what today&#39;s temperature was.”</p><h3> NEW YORK, NY </h3><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bleed
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/projects/narrator/3ce7fbcb-ecc3-4176-9cfd-bfe9b86dae6c.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><p> Heat has an outsize impact on urban areas. In cities such as New York, where asphalt, cement and buildings absorb heat, it will not only feel hotter during the day, but also at night, when a lot of that heat is released, according to Ebi.</p><p> The compact, built-out environments of densely populated cities help create pockets known as heat islands, which experience temperatures that can be several degrees higher than surrounding rural areas. Many elements of city life contribute to this effect, including traffic, industrial facilities, and the heating and cooling of buildings.</p><p> “Think about people who have window air conditioners, and you know the way they work is they take heat from the inside and they dump it outside,” Ebi said. “Air conditioners can make cities hotter as well.” </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><img width="600" height="1040" src="https://s.wsj.net/public/resources/images/10137dca-7b1a-435d-b855-c95d7f3e7990-fallback_app.jpg" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p> More than two-thirds of residents in New York City experience <a href="https://www.climatecentral.org/climate-matters/urban-heat-islands-2023" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noopener">at least 8 degrees Fahrenheit more heat</a> due to the effect, according to the New Jersey-based nonprofit Climate Central.</p><p> City data on the relative risk from extreme-heat events show that residents of the south Bronx, upper Manhattan and central Brooklyn are the most vulnerable. In Brooklyn, Borough President Antonio Reynoso said the vulnerability is largely concentrated in communities of color, including East New York, East Flatbush and Brownsville. City officials have said they hope to <a href="https://climate.cityofnewyork.us/wp-content/uploads/2023/06/PlaNYC-2023-Full-Report.pdf" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noopener">address the extreme-heat problem</a> by, among other things, developing a maximum indoor summer temperature policy by 2030 and planting more trees and expanding the tree canopy cover to 30% from 22%.</p><h3> ATHENS, GREECE </h3><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          edgetoedge
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/projects/narrator/6d07d54e-e523-496b-99ec-e0fe6e0b926b.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><p> Tourists saw their vacations soured by heat waves and wildfires across the Mediterranean last month. Greece experienced a 15-day heat wave—its longest on record, according to Lagouvardos Kostas, meteorologist and research director at the National Observatory of Athens. Temperatures <a href="https://www.esa.int/Applications/Observing_the_Earth/Copernicus/Sentinel-3/Europe_braces_for_sweltering_July" target="_blank" class="icon none">as high as 110 degrees Fahrenheit</a> fried the capital, prompting city officials to intermittently close outdoor archaeological sites such as the Acropolis.</p><p> “It is an open space. It is very exposed to the sun, you have to work to climb to go there too,” Kostas said of the Acropolis. “It&#39;s not an easy task to do it even in fine weather.”</p><p> Officials encouraged tourists and residents to limit their time outside. Some workers were given the option to telecommute rather than risk developing <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/high-temperatures-affect-human-body-11658262757?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">health conditions such as heat stroke</a> , he added. Spain and Italy were among other Mediterranean countries experiencing extreme heat. Catania, in Sicily, saw temperatures exceed 120 degrees Fahrenheit midmonth. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=73DA72E0-DF39-4F23-973C-AEEBEF455473&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fjuly-2023-hottest-month-record-climate-change-5e5b3097&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption"> A massive heat dome across the American Southwest is driving temperatures in Phoenix and Las Vegas to record triple-digit highs. New Maxar satellite photos show how the growth of these cities is contributing to the crushing heat. Illustration: Luca Depardon<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div><p>Europe experienced a similarly scorching and deadly summer in 2022.</p><p> There were <a href="https://www.nature.com/articles/s41591-023-02419-z" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noopener">more than 61,000 heat-related deaths</a> on the continent between the end of May and beginning of September last year, according to a recent study published in the journal Nature Medicine. Mortality was highest in places such as Italy and Greece, and vacationers trying to beat the heat by traveling elsewhere may be taking an economic toll. The number of European tourists planning to travel to Mediterranean destinations <a href="https://etc-corporate.org/news/europeans-adjust-travel-plans-due-to-cost-worries/" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noopener">dropped by 10%</a> compared with last year, according to a European Travel Commission survey.</p><p> Kostas said wildfires burning across Greece—exacerbated by the extreme heat—and the associated smoke are affecting tourism. Multiple blazes forced evacuations in areas south of Athens and on the popular island destination of Rhodes. He added that prolonged, higher temperatures and dry conditions have made the fires larger and more difficult to control.</p><h3> TEHRAN, IRAN </h3><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bleed
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/projects/narrator/65e88f88-2f41-4510-a335-13654fc2d894.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><p> Taps are running dry in Tehran as millions in Iran and neighboring Iraq face water shortages that are being compounded by the effects of rising temperatures.</p><p> “In Iran they are wrestling over the available water,” said Charles Iceland, director for freshwater initiatives at the World Resources Institute, a Washington, DC-based nonprofit. “They have been overexploiting groundwater, and they are actually using it faster than it is replenished.”</p><p> Unsustainable use and management of water resources—to sate a growing population and economy—and inefficient irrigation practices have contributed to scarcity, Iceland said. Roughly 80% of water use goes to agriculture, according to Soroosh Sorooshian, a University of California, Irvine professor of civil and environmental engineering, who grew up in Iran and whose family was in the farming business.</p><p> Farmers generally flood their land using open-air canals, and much of the water is lost to evaporation. As temperatures continue to rise, Iceland said, more of that irrigation water will be lost to evaporation—further taxing water resources. He added that mid-latitude regions including Iran and Iraq are projected to get less rainfall over time as the Earth continues to warm, which may compound the area&#39;s water-scarcity problems.</p><p> A combination of high heat and humidity is an additional issue for the region&#39;s beleaguered population. While temperature highs haven&#39;t exceeded those of Europe and the southern US, researchers say subtropical regions near warm water, including the Middle East, are less hospitable even at the same temperatures. High humidity levels make it more difficult to sweat out excess body heat, preventing us from cooling down, exacerbating heat-related health effects.</p><p> Scientists measure this heat-humidity combo using a metric known as the wet bulb temperature, which CalTech&#39;s Schneider said “approximates what humans can survive.” If this metric exceeds about 95 degrees Fahrenheit, he said, “then humans can&#39;t cool themselves efficiently anymore. Ultimately, you just die.”</p><h3> BEIJING, CHINA </h3><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bleed
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/projects/narrator/a0169004-878c-45c1-8b8e-ef737ccf6863.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><p> In recent weeks, residents in China&#39;s capital and surrounding areas have been hit by a one-two punch of extreme heat and deadly flooding from record rainfall following Typhoon Doksuri.</p><p> The occurrence, intensity and duration of such events are affected by climate change, research shows. Rising temperatures result in increased precipitation. Ultimately the unpredictability of these events makes it harder to manage water, energy and other critical resources in a heavily urbanized country where people and valuable assets are densely clustered, according to Scott Moore, a University of Pennsylvania political scientist and director of China programs and strategic initiatives at the university.</p><p> “There is a good argument that, of the world&#39;s large economies, China is the most vulnerable to climate risk,” Moore said. An <a href="https://www.nature.com/articles/s41467-023-37554-1#Tab1" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noopener">April study</a> published in the journal Nature Communications identified the area around Beijing as being among the most at-risk for high-impact heat waves. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/projects/narrator/c4844e97-42b7-4ff0-b13d-1af3e55998ed.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><p> The aftermath of Doksuri forced more than one million people in Beijing and surrounding areas to evacuate. Meanwhile, consistently high temperatures—Beijing registered a record number of days this year during which temperatures hit or exceeded 95 degrees Fahrenheit—strained electrical grids and exacerbated water shortages.</p><p> A July report from China&#39;s National Climate Center showed the rate of the country&#39;s temperature rise has been higher than the rest of the world&#39;s since the beginning of the 20th century. Extreme high temperature events have increased in frequency and intensity in about the last six decades, as well as a per-decade increase in China&#39;s average annual precipitation during the same period. The biggest threat to Beijing, Moore said, is extreme rainfall that overwhelms the capital&#39;s drainage system, which isn&#39;t built to handle a growing volume of water.</p><p> “There is a real irony of climate extremes here because the principal fear in Beijing has always been not enough water and desertification, but the images that we&#39;re seeing have been absolutely terrifying flooding in the city,” said Jeremy Wallace, a professor of government at Cornell University who focuses on Chinese politics.</p><h3> UTQIAĠVIK, ALASKA</h3><p> Even the Arctic isn&#39;t immune to rising temperatures in a warming world.</p><p> The US&#39;s northernmost city, Utqiaġvik—formerly known as Barrow—north of the Arctic Circle in Alaska, just experienced its hottest July on record. Typically, summer temperatures hover between 40 and 50 degrees Fahrenheit, but on July 23, the daily average temperature hit a record high of 63.5 degrees. That record was just broken again, as the average temperature there on Saturday <a href="https://twitter.com/Climatologist49/status/1688195758380740608?s=20" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noopener">hit 66 degrees</a> , according to Brian Brettschneider, a climate scientist at the National Weather Service Alaska region headquarters.</p><p> “It used to be normal to have a couple inches of snow up there in July,” he said of Utqiaġvik. Other cities around the state, such as Northway, also had their warmest months on record in July. “The last two months have really been kind of big steps up” in a long-term, continuing warming trend worldwide, Brettschneider said, adding that he expects 2024 will be warmer than 2023. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><img width="600" height="940" src="https://s.wsj.net/public/resources/images/76f8a61c-3351-4225-91e2-70962af18733-fallback_app.jpg" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p> Not only does data show Alaska is the fastest warming state due to climate change, but its North Slope is among the fast-warming areas on Earth, Brettschneider said. “It is safe to say the Arctic warms at least twice as fast as the rest of the world,” he added.</p><p> Loss of surrounding sea ice due to rising surface and ocean temperatures has decreased surfaces that act like a mirror for incoming heat from the sun, reflecting solar energy back into space, Brettschneider said. Now more of it is absorbed by the ocean, which further heats up and contributes to more ice melt as part of a feedback loop. This phenomenon is known as Arctic, or polar, amplification. Such ice melt can affect global ocean circulation, and the additional heat filters into the atmosphere, where it gets transported to lower latitudes, affecting sea levels and weather systems.</p><p> “Warmth in Alaska doesn&#39;t stay in Alaska,” he said.</p><p> Write to Aylin Woodward at <a href="mailto:aylin.woodward@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">aylin.woodward@wsj.com</a> , Carl Churchill at <a href="mailto:carl.churchill@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">carl.churchill@wsj.com</a> and Erin Ailworth at <a href="mailto:erin.ailworth@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">erin.ailworth@wsj.com</a></p><div class="media-object scope-web
          inline
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4> SHARE YOUR THOUGHTS</h4><p> <em>Have you found creative ways to beat the heat this summer? Join the conversation below.</em></p></div></div></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Tue, 08 Aug 2023 20:40:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/july-2023-hottest-month-record-climate-change-5e5b3097</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/july-2023-hottest-month-record-climate-change-5e5b3097<author><![CDATA[Aylin WoodwardCarl ChurchillErin Ailworth]]></author><category> wsjscience</category><category> gfx-contrib</category><category> Wildfires</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>气候变化</category><category>Disasters/Accidents</category><category>自然环境</category><category>Floods/Tidal Waves</category><category>全球/世界问题</category><category>Natural Disasters</category><category>风险新闻</category><category>Weather</category><category> SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category> wildfires</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>气候变化</category><category>disasters</category><category> accidents</category><category>自然环境</category><category>floods</category><category> tidal waves</category><category>全球的</category><category>世界问题</category><category>natural disasters</category><category>风险新闻</category><category>weather </category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Colombian Drug Kingpin Sentenced to 45 Years in U.S. Prison]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> Dairo Antonio Úsuga David 此前承认经营犯罪企业和另外两项与毒品有关的指控<!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001119886"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-832076?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">哥伦比亚毒贩戴罗·安东尼奥·乌苏加·大卫去年被哥伦比亚引渡到美国。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：哥伦比亚国家警察/路透社</p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001119886"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/james-fanelli" itemprop="url" rel="author">詹姆斯·法内利</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 8 月 8 日下午 4:39 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/colombian-drug-kingpin-sentenced-to-45-years-in-u-s-prison-4a78fe96"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p>一名曾经是该国头号通缉犯之一的哥伦比亚毒枭周二在布鲁克林联邦法院被判处 45 年监禁，罪名是监督将 100 多吨可卡因走私到中美洲和美国。</p><p> 51 岁的戴罗·安东尼奥·乌苏加·大卫 (Dairo Antonio Úsuga David) <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/colombian-drug-kingpin-pleads-guilty-to-smuggling-cocaine-into-u-s-11674682175?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">一月份承认经营犯罪企业和另外两项与毒品有关的指控</a>，他当时告诉联邦法官，他“从贩毒活动中获得了大量收入和资源”。认罪协议解决了乌苏加·大卫面临的三项联邦起诉。</p><p>美国地区法官多拉·利泽特·伊里扎里 (Dora Lizette Irizarry) 判处 45 年监禁，与布鲁克林美国检察官办公室联邦检察官所寻求的刑期一致。</p><p>检察官在宣判前的一份法庭文件中表示，近十年来，乌苏加·大卫一直是海湾部落的领导人，该部落是一个由至少 1000 名战士组成的农村民兵组织，在哥伦比亚多个省份开展活动。检察官称，乌苏加·大卫在位期间监督毒品贩运，同时恐吓社区。</p><p>检察官在文件中写道：“他下令杀害、绑架和折磨竞争对手，以及他认为配合执法部门侵犯他个人利益的个人。”</p><p>乌苏加·大卫 (Úsuga David) 的律师请求判处 25 年监禁，并在一份法庭文件中表示，法官应该考虑到他们当事人的童年受到暴力和贫困的影响。</p><p> “先生。乌苏加在贫困的环境中长大，几乎没有晋升的机会，自相残杀的暴力不断，哥伦比亚国家在日常生活的最基本方面明显缺位，”律师们说。</p><p>乌苏加·大卫的律师没有立即回应置评请求。</p><p>乌苏加·大卫 (Úsuga David) 又名奥托尼尔 (Otoniel)，经过大规模搜捕<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/colombian-drug-trafficking-kingpin-otoniel-captured-was-wanted-by-u-s-11635091770?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">，于 2021 年在哥伦比亚和巴拿马边境附近的一个藏身处被捕</a>。</p><p>联邦调查人员多年来一直追捕他，美国悬赏 500 万美元寻找导致他被捕的信息。 <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/suspected-colombian-drug-kingpin-extradited-to-u-s-11651787114?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">他去年被引渡到美国</a>。</p><p>写信给 James Fanelli： <a href="mailto:james.fanelli@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">james.fanelli@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Tue, 08 Aug 2023 20:39:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/colombian-drug-kingpin-sentenced-to-45-years-in-us-prison-4a78fe96</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/colombian-drug-kingpin-sentenced-to-45-years-in-us-prison-4a78fe96<author><![CDATA[James Fanelli]]></author><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>犯罪/法律诉讼</category><category>毒品贩运/交易</category><category>犯罪企业</category><category>贩运/走私</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>犯罪</category><category>合法举动</category><category>贩毒</category><category>交易</category><category>犯罪企业</category><category>贩卖</category><category>走私</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Niger Junta Snubs U.S.-Backed Peace Mission]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>政变领导人拒绝欢迎旨在讨论回归文官政府的代表团，增加了地区战争的风险<!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001119036"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="560" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-831613?width=860&amp;height=560" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">和平使团原定于周二抵达尼日尔首都尼亚美。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：法新社/盖蒂图片社</p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001119036"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline">作者： <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/drew-hinshaw" itemprop="url" rel="author">德鲁·欣肖</a></span>和<span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/benoit-faucon" itemprop="url" rel="author">伯努瓦·福孔</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">更新于 2023 年 8 月 8 日下午 3:12（美国东部时间） </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/niger-junta-snubs-u-s-backed-peace-mission-a79f76e5"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p>尼日尔新军政府周二拒绝允许美国支持的和平使团从邻国尼日利亚出发访问，称无法保证他们在首都的安全，首都的道路现在被民族主义青年封锁。</p><p>军政府对其他西非政府派出的代表团的冷落加剧了西非沿海文职政府与该地区内陆军事政权之间爆发战争的风险。</p><p>由尼日利亚前国家元首率领的代表团原定于周二抵达尼日尔首都尼亚美，距该国<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/niger-coup-president-us-fumble-russia-africa-86cf1454-33d18bc?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">总统卫队夺权</a>两周后。在那里，他们希望说服军政府领导人采取措施<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/niger-coup-leaders-detain-ministers-party-officials-6ba1efa1?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">恢复文官统治</a>，并防止与非洲人口最多的邻国尼日利亚<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/france-prepares-to-evacuate-european-citizens-from-coup-hit-niger-d46774af?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">发生武装冲突的风险</a>。</p><p>尼日利亚在西非国家经济共同体其他 10 个文职政府的支持下，威胁称，如果军政府领导人不下台，将使用武力推翻军政府。周四，尼日利亚将主办西非总统和外交部长紧急会议，讨论下一步行动。</p><p>尼日尔外交部表示，公众对尼日利亚试图扭转政变的愤怒将危及代表团的安全。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="480" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-831650?width=700&amp;height=480" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">一些尼日尔人对尼亚美军事政变表示支持。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：法新社/盖蒂图片社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>过去几天，成群的年轻人在连接尼亚美机场和首都的道路上以及通往总统府的大道上设置了路障，搜查汽车，并发誓要保卫国家。反对政变的居民表示，他们害怕抗议或表达自己的观点。</p><p> “我们这里有数百人 24 小时守卫，”在尼亚美中部守卫路障的支持政变武装分子易卜拉欣·纳迈瓦 (Ibrahim Namaiwa) 说。 “任何对士兵发动战争的人都必须先杀死我们。”</p><p>周一，尼日尔军政府欢迎来自布基纳法索和马里军事政权的代表团，这两个与莫斯科结盟的邻国誓言保卫尼日尔免受西非国家区域联盟西非经共体的干预。俄罗斯公开反对对尼日尔进行武装干预，其瓦格纳雇佣军组织表示愿意帮助军政府自卫。</p><p>瓦格纳领导人叶夫根尼·普里戈任（Yevgeny Prigozhin）在针对尼日尔新军政府领导人的音频消息中说：“请随时给我们打电话。”该消息于周二在与该组织相关的 Telegram 频道上分享。</p><p>支持西非经共体和平使命的美国在尼日尔拥有约 1,100 名士兵和数个无人机基地，直到上个月政变之前，尼日尔一直是美国在撒哈拉地区的顶级反恐伙伴。美国已花费约 5 亿美元建设尼日尔军队，其中包括价值 1.1 亿美元的阿加德兹无人机基地。</p><p>美国已与至少一名军政府高级成员进行会谈，以说服政变领导人回归民主统治。周一，代理副国务卿维多利亚·纽兰前往尼日尔会见军政府，试图通过外交手段解决紧张局势。</p><p> “这些谈话非常坦诚，有时也相当困难，”她告诉记者。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-831616?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">西非国家和西方政府实施的金融制裁开始产生影响。尼亚美的一个市场。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：法新社/盖蒂图片社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>周二，尼日利亚官员试图压制有关军事干预的言论，但他们表示军事干预仍然是西非经共体的最后手段。</p><p>尼日利亚总统发言人阿朱里·恩格拉莱 (Ajuri Ngelale) 表示：“虽然西非经共体的谈判桌上没有任何选项，但没有任何投机性的猜测可以阻止正在进行的调解努力，以实现尼日尔共和国和平恢复民主统治。”</p><p>尼日利亚的文官政府——与塞内加尔、科特迪瓦和其他西非民主国家的文官政府一样——担心未能扭转尼日尔的政变将激励其他国家的军官夺取政权。就在过去三年里，马里发生了两次政变，布基纳法索又发生了两次政变，几内亚发生了一次，乍得又发生了一次。</p><p>更广泛地说，这个拥有 4.41 亿人口的地区正面临着青年人普遍失业、城市拥挤以及对未来繁荣的悲观预期的浪潮。基地组织和伊斯兰国盟友叛乱分子还在马里、布基纳法索以及尼日利亚和尼日尔发动了数千次袭击。</p><p>具有超凡魅力的军事统治者将自己视为技术官僚和亲西方文职政府的有吸引力的替代方案。 <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/niger-coup-us-russia-africa-86cf1454?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">俄罗斯也填补了这一空缺</a>，为那些认为自己没有从与巴黎长达一个世纪的经济和政治关系中受益的前法国殖民地提供了自己的反殖民伙伴关系。</p><p>一些尼亚美居民表示，虽然他们最初并不支持政变，但他们认为军事统治比旨在恢复民主的武装冲突更好。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=7F7AB6E6-CE60-46D3-B0B7-C075C1006060&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fniger-junta-snubs-u-s-backed-peace-mission-a79f76e5&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption"> Coup leaders in Niger announced a closure of its airspace, causing flights to reroute around the country. It comes as the Sunday deadline set by other West African countries for the military junta to back down passed. Photo: Flightradar24.com<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div><p>“我没有呼吁发动政变，但既然政变已经发生，就应该允许尼日尔人民在不受外界干扰的情况下解决问题，”进口商奥马鲁·马拉姆·伊萨 (Umaru Malam Isa) 表示。 “虽然我不喜欢政变，但这可能是尼日尔实现发展的唯一途径。”</p><p>与此同时，政变的反对者表示，一波对政治领导人盟友的逮捕浪潮以及对最初的民主抗议活动的暴力镇压使他们无法发声，尽管西非经共体和西方政府实施的贸易和金融制裁已开始咬。尼亚美的一名医生表示，军政府冻结了除水电以外的其他支出，他担心药物很快就会耗尽。</p><p> “像我这样反对政变的人都不敢表达自己的观点，”医生说。 “只有一侧携带武器。”</p><p>写信给 Drew Hinshaw ( <a href="mailto:drew.hinshaw@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">drew.hinshaw@wsj.com)</a>和 Benoit Faucon ( <a href="mailto:benoit.faucon@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">benoit.faucon@wsj.com</a> )</p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Tue, 08 Aug 2023 19:12:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/niger-junta-snubs-us-backed-peace-mission-a79f76e5</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/niger-junta-snubs-us-backed-peace-mission-a79f76e5<author><![CDATA[Drew HinshawBenoit Faucon]]></author><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>国家/公共安全</category><category>叛乱</category><category>国际关系</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>风险新闻</category><category>军事行动</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>national</category><category>公安</category><category>叛乱</category><category>国际关系</category><category>政治</category><category>国内政治</category><category>风险新闻</category><category>军事行动</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Latin American Countries Aim to Curb Amazon Deforestation]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>巴西总统接待地区领导人，因为雨林面临失去帮助抵消气候变化能力的风险<figure><img src="https://images.wsj.net/im-831814/?width=1278&amp;size=1" alt="长期以来，亚马逊雨林吸收的碳多于释放的碳，但近 20% 的原始森林现已消失。" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>长期以来，亚马逊雨林吸收的碳多于释放的碳，但近 20% 的原始森林现已消失。 UESLEI MARCELINO/路透社<span>UESLEI MARCELINO/路透社</span></figcaption></figure><!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001119095"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001119095"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline">作者： <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/samantha-pearson" itemprop="url" rel="author">萨曼莎·皮尔森</a></span>和<span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/luciana-magalhaes" itemprop="url" rel="author">卢西亚娜·马加哈斯</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 8 月 8 日下午 1:38 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/latin-american-countries-aim-to-curb-amazon-deforestation-c479cfd5"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bigtophero
"></div><p>圣保罗——共享亚马逊雨林的拉丁美洲国家周二在巴西丛林城市贝伦举行了为期两天的会议，旨在制止<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/amazonian-destruction-risesbefore-brazil-presidential-election-11663166106?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">森林砍伐</a>，许多科学家指责森林砍伐加速了气候变化。</p><p>巴西拥有<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/brazil-battles-for-amazon-tribe-known-as-guardian-of-the-rainforest-5a66569d?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">世界上 60% 的最大雨林</a>，该国为亚马逊其他地区的国家（秘鲁、哥伦比亚、玻利维亚、委内瑞拉、厄瓜多尔、圭亚那和苏里南）的总统和高级官员举行了会议。此次峰会是亚马逊合作条约组织 14 年来的首次峰会，该组织源于 1978 年亚马逊国家签署的一项条约，旨在促进该地区的和谐发展。法国驻巴西利亚大使代表法国负责管理南美洲东北部的法属圭亚那。</p><p>此次会议召开之际，巴西总统路易斯·伊纳西奥·卢拉·达席尔瓦寻求通过这项已有 45 年历史的条约，将巴西定位为全球反对森林砍伐的主要声音，并成为非洲大陆跨境环境合作的推动者。</p><p> “恢复和扩大这种合作从未如此紧迫——这是我们时代的挑战，”达席尔瓦在周二的开幕致辞中说。</p><p>其他拥有大片热带森林的国家，如印度尼西亚、刚果共和国和刚果民主共和国，预计将与挪威和德国一起参加会议，这些国家为毁林计划做出了贡献。今年将在迪拜主办<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-a-e-names-oil-chief-to-run-cop28-climate-summit-11673542016?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">联合国气候峰会的</a>阿拉伯联合酋长国也将出席。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-831850?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">巴西总统路易斯·伊纳西奥·卢拉·达席尔瓦在贝伦峰会上。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：安东尼奥·拉塞尔达/Shutterstock</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>亚马逊雨林的面积是印度的两倍，长期以来吸收的碳多于释放的碳，成为全球气候变化的重要制动因素。但随着近 20% 的原始森林消失，追踪森林的科学家表示，亚马逊可能已经接近所谓的不可逆转的临界点，届时它将变得干燥，最终变成稀树草原。影响可能是全球性的。气候科学家将森林丧失归咎于全球变暖，美国环境保护署表示，这解释了为什么热浪在美国等国家变得越来越普遍。</p><p>巴西国家空间研究所的初步数据显示，巴西亚马逊地区的森林砍伐达到自达席尔瓦一月上任以来四年来的最低水平，今年前六个月与去年同期相比下降了约34%研究，称为INPE。尽管达席尔瓦发誓要到 2030 年将丛林破坏降至零，但他认为，这一目标不能以牺牲巴西亚马逊地区约 3000 万居民的生计为代价。</p><p>达席尔瓦认为，巴西必须利用国外的融资和投资在亚马逊地区建立新的绿色经济，并发展受监管的碳市场。巴西依靠外国捐款来帮助其资金不足的环境执法机构运作，这些机构使用直升机、无人机和其他设备来监测广大地区的非法森林砍伐。</p><p>达席尔瓦在一份政府声明中表示：“我们想要告诉世界我们将如何处理我们的森林，以及世界必须采取哪些措施来帮助我们。”达席尔瓦表示，他计划向富裕国家施压，要求它们履行在<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/final-draft-of-global-climate-change-deal-is-complete-1449906731?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">2015年巴黎气候协议</a>中做出的承诺，每年提供1000亿美元帮助发展中国家应对气候变化。</p><p>包括哥伦比亚和秘鲁在内的其他拉丁美洲国家也制定了森林砍伐目标，但面临着非法采矿和贩毒团伙的严重挑战，这些团伙加强了对森林的控制，联合国最近将其称为“毒品森林砍伐”。</p><p>科学家表示，解决森林砍伐问题是南美洲面临的最紧迫任务之一。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-831817?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">一名巴西官员在检查巴西普拉卡斯的一家锯木厂。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：UESLEI MARCELINO/路透社</p></figcaption></figure></div><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-831819?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">巴西依靠外国捐款来帮助其资金不足的环境执法机构运作。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：《华尔街日报》的托马索·普罗蒂</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>INPE 研究员 Luciana Gatti 在 2021 年发表的一项研究显示，亚马逊东南部地区森林砍伐严重的地区已经不再发挥碳吸收器的作用，而是成为碳源。INPE 使用卫星跟踪森林砍伐情况。</p><p>丹尼尔·内普斯塔德说，亚马逊雨林影响着世界各地的天气模式，随着森林砍伐的加剧，这可能会使极端天气事件变得更加普遍。</p>他是加州地球创新研究所的负责人，在亚马逊工作了 30 多年。<p></p><p>内普斯塔德说：“森林是一个全球空调装置……一个影响世界各地天气的巨大热处理机器。”他补充说，所有领导人愿意开会讨论这个问题本身就是一个“非常积极的成果”。</p><p>今年， <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/extreme-heat-waves-across-the-world-photos-7cc1544d?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">致命的热浪</a>扰乱了美国、欧洲和亚洲大部分地区的日常生活，而南美洲冬季异常高温导致安第斯山脉的积雪融化。</p><p>环保人士表示，区域协调至关重要。在亚马逊深处，土著社区经常跨越边界，伐木者和犯罪团伙可以自由活动，一国的努力很容易因邻国的努力而变得无效。</p><div class="media-object scope-web
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4> SHARE YOUR THOUGHTS</h4><p><em>是否采取了足够的措施来制止亚马逊地区的森林砍伐？ Join the conversation below.</em></p></div></div><p>就在一年前，当达席尔瓦的右翼前任</p>贾尔·博尔索纳罗担任总统。博尔索纳罗开玩笑地称自己为“电锯船长”，他削减了环境执法资金，并对外国试图影响他对亚马逊的管理工作感到愤怒，尽管他呼吁外国<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/brazils-climate-overture-to-biden-pay-us-not-to-raze-amazon-11618997400?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">为砍伐森林活动提供资金</a>。<p></p><p>根据 INPE 的数据，在这位保守派领导人的领导下，四年内，一片比佛蒙特州还大的森林被毁。</p><p>政治学家表示，去年 10 月达席尔瓦的当选将南美大部分地区置于一群松散联盟的左翼领导人手中，从而缓和了有关亚马逊地区问题的区域谈判，而该问题从未产生过切实的合作。</p><p>诚然，参加贝伦峰会的国家之间存在着冲突点。</p><p>虽然达席尔瓦正在考虑开发亚马逊河口附近的海上石油资源，以帮助降低国内燃料成本，但他的哥伦比亚同行古斯塔沃·佩特罗上个月呼吁阻止该地区所有新的石油开发。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="467" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-831860?width=700&amp;height=467" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">巴西里约热内卢州一家炼油厂附近的牛群正在吃草。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：佩德罗·普拉多/彭博新闻</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>“作为国家元首，我们必须确保亚马逊停止新的石油和天然气勘探，” <a href="https://www.miamiherald.com/opinion/op-ed/article277248923.html" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noopener">佩特罗上个月在《迈阿密先驱报》上写道</a>。 “即使我们正在解决国内的基本社会问题，但生活成本危机和猖獗的通货膨胀加剧了这些问题，我们也必须表现出勇气。”</p><p>巴西气候观测站的环保组织联盟负责人马西奥·阿斯特里尼表示，亚马逊流域国家可能会在保护土著社区、打击边境犯罪以及支持科学研究以更好地了解森林方面找到共同点。</p><p> “这些国家处于不同的政治局势……但他们都在议程中找到了同意这一点的空间，并聚在一起讨论这些敏感问题，”阿斯特里尼说。</p><p>不过，阿斯特里尼说，他们最大的共同点是希望让更富裕的国家帮助支付所有这些费用。</p><p> “给我钱——这是他们都会异口同声地说的一件事，”他说。</p><p>写信给 Samantha Pearson（ <a href="mailto:samantha.pearson@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">samantha.pearson@wsj.com）</a>和 Luciana Magalhaes（ <a href="mailto:luciana.magalhaes@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">luciana.magalhaes@wsj.com</a> ）</p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Tue, 08 Aug 2023 17:38:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/latin-american-countries-aim-to-curb-amazon-deforestation-c479cfd5</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/latin-american-countries-aim-to-curb-amazon-deforestation-c479cfd5<author><![CDATA[Samantha PearsonLuciana Magalhaes]]></author><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>气候变化</category><category>国际关系</category><category>自然环境</category><category>森林砍伐</category><category>全球/世界问题</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>卢西安娜·加蒂</category><category>丹尼尔·内普斯塔德</category><category>贾尔·博尔索纳罗</category><category>古斯塔沃·佩特罗</category><category>马西奥·阿斯特里尼</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>气候变化</category><category>国际关系</category><category>自然环境</category><category>砍伐森林</category><category>全球的</category><category>世界问题</category><category>政治</category><category>国内政治</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[A Famous Hippie Freetown Is Ganging Up on Drug Criminals]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>哥本哈根的克里斯蒂安尼亚街区吸引了大批游客和顽固的犯罪分子<figure><img src="https://images.wsj.net/im-831451/?width=1278&amp;size=1" alt="哥本哈根克里斯蒂安尼亚的居民动员起来，关闭了名为 Pusher Street 的露天大麻市场。" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>哥本哈根克里斯蒂安尼亚的居民动员起来，关闭了名为 Pusher Street 的露天大麻市场。 <span></span></figcaption></figure><!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001117853"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001117853"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline">作者： <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/sune-engel-rasmussen" itemprop="url" rel="author">Sune Engel Rasmussen</a></span> |詹纳斯·恩格尔 (Janus Engel) 为《华尔街日报》拍摄的照片</div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 8 月 8 日上午 8:06 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/a-famous-hippie-freetown-is-ganging-up-on-drug-criminals-6f630367"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bigtophero
"></div><p>哥本哈根——50 年来，丹麦首都克里斯蒂安尼亚 (Christiania) 是一个无政府主义、自由奔放的公社，因其露天大麻市场而享誉全球，吸引了来自世界各地的游客，同时还有顽固的犯罪分子和警方的定期镇压。</p><p>现在，一群居民奋起反抗控制了该行业的帮派，进行了一次危险的秘密行动，旨在关闭著名的普舍街。</p><p>近年来，有组织的犯罪分子将克里斯蒂安尼亚的大部分居民赶出了利润丰厚的大麻贸易，使北欧最大的旅游景点之一和丹麦宽容的象征变得恶化。</p><p>在发生一系列日益严重的暴力事件（包括几起杀戮）之后，许多居民已经受够了。周二黎明前，大约 50 名基督教徒（公社居民的称呼）在夜深人静时聚集在一起，观看他们订购的起重机使用集装箱和混凝土墙封锁普舍街的入口，几个小时后毒贩就会到达这里。开始一天的工作。</p><p>活动人士表示，“采取这一行动是希望将克里斯蒂安尼亚从帮派和铁杆犯罪分子的暴政中解放出来。”他们补充说，他们这样做是冒着自身安全的巨大风险的。 “我们都是普通人，必须去上班，为孩子们打包饭盒。这些团伙准备使用暴力并杀人，以保护他们的收入和领土。” </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-831475?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">克里斯蒂安尼亚的许多居民担心封锁街道行动后几天内毒贩的报复。</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>克里斯蒂安尼亚的居民和毒贩之间的对决是丹麦和欧洲毒品市场<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/how-peaceful-sweden-became-europes-gun-murder-capital-a5b500a7?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">日益扩大和暴力</a>的结果。这也标志着欧洲最激进、最持久的社会实验之一的转折点，该实验自 1971 年成立以来一直在违反法律的情况下生存下来，当时一群嬉皮士占领了一个废弃的军营，并建立了一个基于自我保护的反资本主义避风港。治理、自由思想和大麻合法化。</p><p> “我们需要真相时刻，”参与周二行动的一名居民说。 “我们已经从绿色能源、艺术、文化和 LGBTQ 权利的榜样，变成了我们所有的社区会议都在讨论 Pusher 街的暴力事件。”</p><p>克里斯蒂安尼亚早期的大麻贸易是由嬉皮士驾驶破旧的大众货车从亚洲运往哥本哈根推动的。如今，每年价值约 1.5 亿美元的大麻通过挤在 100 米长的鹅卵石步行街 Pusher 街的大约 30 个胶合板摊位流通。瑞典马尔默大学犯罪学副教授、克里斯蒂安尼亚问题专家 Kim Møller 表示，该行业约占丹麦大麻经济总量的三分之二，不过他补充说，没有人知道该业务的确切规模。</p><p>整个非洲大陆的大麻市场正在蓬勃发展。根据欧洲毒品和毒瘾监测中心的数据，2021 年，欧洲当局缉获了近 1,100 吨大麻脂和大麻草本，这是十年来的最高水平，这反映出其他更危险的麻醉品贸易的增加， <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/police-raids-target-italian-mafia-across-europe-e4b5209d?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">尤其是可卡因</a>。根据 EMCDDA 的数据，在过去的十年中，欧洲查获的大麻的效力也显着增加， <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424052970203646004577213593506293770?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">长期成瘾的潜在危害也</a>随之增加。</p><p>贸易规模的不断扩大与克里斯蒂娜过去的生活格格不入。这个拥有约 850 名居民的社区坐落在丹麦首都一些最令人垂涎​​的房地产上，占地 34 公顷，距离议会大厦不到一英里。该公社禁止汽车通行，色彩缤纷、奇特的房屋、马厩和素食餐厅星罗棋布地分布在大湖泊周围，周围环绕着茂密的绿色植被。</p><p> Fleur Frilund, a 27-year-old copywriting student, moved into Christiania about six years ago, attracted to its proximity to nature and embrace of artists, freethinkers and old virtues such as craftsmanship, as many people built and renovated their own homes.</p><p> “It&#39;s a radically different way of living, compared to the big-city mentality just on the other side of the fence,” she said in an interview in her third-floor apartment, which previously belonged to a navy colonel.</p><p> It is this lifestyle that residents say they are trying to salvage. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bleed
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/projects/narrator/71c21a2b-c71b-4263-8d14-cdebb8974f18.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><p> On Sunday, two days before the operation, about a dozen activists met in a private home, behind drawn curtains, to complete their battle plan. Over coffee, the atmosphere was tense. Nobody touched the spread of hummus and freshly baked buns.</p><p> A middle-aged man&#39;s hands were visibly shaking. Many worried about retaliation from drug dealers in the days following the operation. One activist had sent his wife and children away for the week. In case of a confrontation during the operation, they agreed to only call the police if weapons appeared. One young activist proposed bringing along fire extinguishers in case the drug dealers set dogs on them.</p><p> In the end, the predawn operation ensured that no drug dealers confronted the activists—young and old, men and women—as they moved around Christiania, guiding the shipping containers into place in the dark. While younger participants trashed cannabis stalls, middle-age residents spray-painted the containers: “Pusher Street is closed.”</p><p> “Christianites have not turned against free cannabis,” an activist said. “But Pusher Street doesn&#39;t help the cause for free hash in any way. It&#39;s a worst-case scenario of what free cannabis can lead to.” </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-831467?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> A mural of a young Christiania resident who was killed in July in 2021. </p></figcaption></figure></div><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-831462?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Emmerik Warburg has lived in Christiania since 1974.</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> Despite its anarchic origins, Christiania has maintained its own rules that banned cars, hard drugs, motorcycle gang insignia and bulletproof vests. In Pusher Street, photography is prohibited, as is running, so the drug dealers can tell when a police raid is under way.</p><p> Evicting residents from Christiania is nearly impossible. Some 40 to 50 residents are actively involved in the cannabis trade, according to Copenhagen police, and like other Christianites they have the right to veto any major decisions proposed in community meetings, and have protected Pusher Street.</p><p> Over the years, government pressure has forced Christiania to gradually relinquish some of its autonomy. In 2011, after seven years of failed negotiations with the state, residents agreed to purchase the land they lived on, formally legalizing their status as landowners. Unanimously refusing to buy property individually, they instead purchased it collectively through a fund for about $12 million, raising some of it through the sale of shares to the public.</p><p> “We are proof that poor people are also able to live in the center of the city,” said Emmerik Warburg, 70, who has lived in Christiania since 1974.</p><p> For decades, however, police raids have targeted Pusher Street, resulting in numerous deaths of residents and dealers. As the violence accompanying the trade worsened, police have continued to raid Pusher Street several times a week, often with brute force, only to see stalls re-erected and hidden hash re-emerge from hiding places as soon as they leave. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bleed
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/projects/narrator/87f5a147-79bd-4611-aaf8-073d5a2f4872.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><p> With criminal groups repeatedly clashing over Pusher Street, the freetown has become a battleground for Denmark&#39;s largest organized gangs. An influx of young outsiders has gradually pried control of the drug market from Christiania&#39;s own dealers.</p><p> Some gang members openly use hard drugs, carry weapons and employ minors, all of which contravene the commune&#39;s rules.</p><p> When a young man by a stall was shot and killed last year, following the killing of a young resident the year before, many were rattled.</p><p> “As long as we had our friends down there, we could keep up,” Warburg, who works for Christiania&#39;s self-governing administration, said about Pusher Street. “They violate the moral code of Christiania.”</p><p> Authorities and Christiania accuse each other of not doing enough to restore order, but have recently reached a rare agreement to potentially cooperate. At a meeting in June, residents agreed with the police, Justice Ministry and the city of Copenhagen—authorities that the group has been at loggerheads with for five decades—to set out an agreement to eventually clear Pusher Street.</p><p> “The violence and crime around Pusher Street have reached a level that we neither can nor want to accept,” said Lord Mayor of Copenhagen Sophie Hæstorp Andersen.</p><p> The activists didn&#39;t harbor illusions that Tuesday&#39;s action would permanently close down Pusher Street, but said they hoped it would serve as an invitation to the police and politicians to get serious about trying—even if it means the drug trade moves to other parts of Copenhagen, bringing violence in its wake. “It&#39;s a classic drug-crime dilemma: violence versus consumption,” said Møller, the criminologist. “You&#39;re damned if you do, damned if you don&#39;t.”</p><p> Write to Sune Engel Rasmussen at <a href="mailto:sune.rasmussen@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">sune.rasmussen@wsj.com</a> </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-831470?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Christiania in Copenhagen, as seen from the lakeside.</p></figcaption></figure></div></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Tue, 08 Aug 2023 12:06:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/a-famous-hippie-freetown-is-ganging-up-on-drug-criminals-6f630367</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/a-famous-hippie-freetown-is-ganging-up-on-drug-criminals-6f630367<author><![CDATA[Sune Engel Rasmussen]]></author><category>休闲/艺术/酒店</category><category>旅游</category><category>Drug/Substance Use/Abuse</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>社会/社区</category><category>犯罪/法律诉讼</category><category>毒品贩运/交易</category><category>Gangs</category><category>犯罪企业</category><category>社会问题</category><category>贩运/走私</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category> drug</category><category> substance use</category><category>虐待</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>社会</category><category>社区</category><category>犯罪</category><category>合法举动</category><category>贩毒</category><category>交易</category><category>gangs</category><category>犯罪企业</category><category>社会问题</category><category>贩卖</category><category>走私</category><category>闲暇</category><category>艺术</category><category>款待</category><category>旅游</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[U.S.-Made Cluster Munitions Fuel Ukrainian Counteroffensive]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>炸弹正在摧毁基辅军队艰难推进地区的俄罗斯战壕和炮兵系统<!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001117870"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-831501?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">乌克兰斯拉维扬斯克郊区的一艘集束炸弹运输车。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：Michal Burza/Zuma Press </p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001117870"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline">作者： <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/ian-lovett" itemprop="url" rel="author">伊恩·洛维特</a></span>和<span class="author" itemprop="name">尼基塔·尼古拉连科</span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 8 月 8 日上午 7:23 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-made-cluster-munitions-fuel-ukrainian-counteroffensive-c45c305f"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p>乌克兰扎波罗热——在几周毫无进展之后，新交付的<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-to-send-cluster-munitions-to-bolster-ukraines-fight-against-dug-in-russians-d2dd292f?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">美国制造的集束弹药</a>为乌克兰夺回被俄罗斯占领的领土的行动注入了新的动力。</p><p>乌克兰士兵表示，他们使用集束炸弹袭击了俄罗斯步兵、车辆群和其他目标的集中区域，为地面进攻扫清了道路。集束炸弹可发射数十颗较小的子炸弹，比普通炮弹能在更大范围内造成破坏。</p><p>面对广阔的雷区和莫斯科优越的空中力量，基辅的<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/ukraines-stalled-offensive-puts-biden-in-uneasy-political-position-6f686ab5?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">反攻行动一直举步维艰</a>，这阻碍了利用西方提供的坦克和装甲车大规模攻击和突破俄罗斯军队的防线。</p><p>虽然集束炸弹本身不会使战场力量平衡决定性地向有利于乌克兰的方向倾斜，但士兵们表示，它们帮助他们<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/ukraine-adopts-slow-approach-to-counteroffensive-our-problem-everywhere-is-the-sky-a2e51d7a?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">重新夺回了他们一直难以到达的俄罗斯阵地</a>。</p><p>这些弹药加上战术的改变，使乌克兰军队能够在某些地方推进到俄罗斯主要防线的打击距离内。这一进展伴随着巨大的伤亡。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=EDA02BF5-0836-4277-AB7C-10442F70192F&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fu-s-made-cluster-munitions-fuel-ukrainian-counteroffensive-c45c305f&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption"> 《华尔街日报》解释了集束弹药背后的技术以及它们为何引起人道主义担忧。插图：雅各布·亚历山大·尼尔森<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div><p>“集束炸弹很好。他们是有效的，”侦察连连长阿纳托利·哈琴科上尉说。 “但俄罗斯人挖得很深，而且学得很快。”</p><p>哈琴科说，俄罗斯的战壕可能有7英尺深，俄罗斯人正在通过更分散的兵力来适应，以避免重大损失。</p><p>最近扎波罗热市东南部Robobyne村周围的战斗证明了乌克兰军火库中新武器的有效性。</p><p> 7月下旬，一个排被困在村庄东边，遭受了俄罗斯的猛烈炮火。该部队通过无线电向指挥官发出请求，要求撤退。他告诉排要躲起来。集束炸弹飞过头顶。一名士兵说，他听到了类似下雨的声音，随后俄罗斯广播频道出现混乱。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><img width="600" height="1262" src="https://s.wsj.net/public/resources/images/ad8ecb39-26bb-4a4d-b98b-c4700b367059-fallback_app.jpg" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p> “他们大喊，‘我们有很多伤员。我们需要撤离。我们正在撤退，”乌克兰士兵说道。士兵们说，该排向前推进，占领了俄罗斯阵地。</p><p>乌克兰仍然没有达到俄罗斯最强大的防御、一系列战壕、坦克陷阱和其他障碍。军事专家表示，乌克兰可能需要<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/german-made-leopard-tanks-for-ukraine-are-politically-symbolic-but-no-game-changer-11674151572?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">豹2坦克</a>和其他西方提供的装甲车来突破这些防线。</p><p>为了保护这些车辆，乌克兰军方改变了战术，因为六月初乌克兰军队在雷区大量损失了这些车辆。现在，步兵在其他部队调来的预备队的支持下，正在步行穿过雷区，带领前进。</p><p>士兵们表示，随着战略变化，乌克兰军队现在相信他们有机会取得突破。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><img width="600" height="2770" src="https://s.wsj.net/public/resources/images/16d21f69-0148-4de6-8efa-d7313e2e8cf8-fallback_app.jpg" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p>上周，33 岁的步兵列兵亚历山大 (Oleksandr) 所率领的 16 人排向俄罗斯阵地推进，遭到俄罗斯机枪的猛烈射击。乌克兰人被迫撤退。</p><p>然后乌克兰用集束弹药击中了隐藏俄罗斯军队的林木线。灌木丛和草着火了。当下一次攻击开始时，亚历山大可以看到他正在射击的俄罗斯人，他们不再隐藏在灌木丛中。</p><p>他的排占领了该阵地，杀死了大约 12 名俄罗斯人，并俘虏了另外几人。他说，囚犯们因集束炸弹而遭受脑震荡和烧伤。</p><p>他说：“使用集束炸弹，发射三枪，树木就会完全倒塌。”他补充说，集束炸弹袭击后，来袭的火力减少了。他说，由于这些弹药会造成大范围的破坏，因此它们不需要那么准确才能有效。</p><p> “即使你错过了一点，它仍然有效，”他说。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-831503?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">收集了去年袭击乌克兰哈尔科夫的俄罗斯火箭碎片，包括集束弹。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：Libkos/美联社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>美国驻欧洲陆军前司令本·霍奇斯中将表示，美国发送的是集束弹药，而不是更多的榴弹炮弹药，而<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-ramps-up-howitzer-shell-production-to-supply-ukraine-replenish-stockpiles-1e6dce54?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">西方国家的榴弹炮弹药已经不足</a>。他预计集束炸弹会更有效。它们是为一支寡不敌众的军队而设计的，就像现在的乌克兰一样。</p><p> “对付大规模编队的部分方法就是使用这种可分散的弹药，”他说。 “如果你坐在露天战壕中，你将为这些事情付出巨大的代价。”</p><p>最近发布在社交媒体上的视频显示，乌克兰集束弹药袭击后，俄罗斯士兵身上有六处小伤。霍奇斯表示，这些炸弹也符合他所认为的乌克兰针对俄罗斯火炮的战略转变。</p><p>他说：“只要炮兵能够到达，这些炮弹就能真正摧毁它们。”</p><p>这些武器被100多个国家禁止，美国向乌克兰运送这些武器的决定受到了人道主义组织的严厉批评。并非所有的小炸弹都会立即爆炸，有时它们还会伤害多年后遇到的人。</p><p>俄罗斯军队在整个战争期间一直在使用集束弹药：携带这些弹药的白色弹壳伸出全国各地的田野。据联合国报告称，乌克兰去年也曾多次使用过它们。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><img width="600" height="610" src="https://s.wsj.net/public/resources/images/b0723491-abf8-41f3-aadf-419194652de4-fallback_app.jpg" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p>一名发射过集束弹药的炮兵部队士兵表示，这些弹药在战场上最为有效，因为它们分布在更广泛的区域。</p><p> “集束弹药很重要，但它们不是一个转折点，”他说，并补充说，针对不同情况使用不同类型的火炮很重要。</p><p>步兵表示，通常情况下，炮兵部队会在步行推进之前向俄罗斯阵地发射不同的弹药。尽管如此，Robotyne 的进步所付出的人力成本仍然是巨大的。</p><p> “我们正在用尸体在田野上排雷，”另一个新组建的、接受西方训练的旅的排长说。 “太糟糕了。”</p><p>步兵奥莱克桑德·佩尔辛 (Oleksandr Pershin) 表示，在罗布坦以东的田野里，集束弹药摧毁树木覆盖的能力是无价的。他说，在最近一次对俄罗斯阵地的攻击中，腰部高度以上的树已经没有了。</p><p> “其他一切都被摧毁了，”他说，“主要是集束弹药造成的。”</p><p>他说，一旦他的部队占据了这个位置，他们就试图继续穿过树林，向俄罗斯的下一条防线推进。在 24 小时内，他们进行了一系列攻击，但不断被击退，因为俄罗斯人用机枪扫射他们。</p><p>最终，他们被命令在原地挖战壕。</p><p>当 34 岁的 Pershin 正在挖掘时，一枚火箭落在他附近，弹片溅到他身上，把他送往医院。当他说话时，他的手臂上吊着绷带，全身的伤口都缠着绷带。他说，参与袭击的 60 人中有 45 人受伤或死亡。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=A74E51B6-FB53-4840-BB4D-2B1A0CCC986B&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fu-s-made-cluster-munitions-fuel-ukrainian-counteroffensive-c45c305f&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption">官员称，俄罗斯周一对波克罗夫斯克镇发动袭击，造成至少 7 人死亡、80 多人受伤。罢工损坏了公寓、酒店、餐馆、商店和行政大楼。照片：Viacheslav Ratynskyi/Reuters<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div><p class="articleTagLine">——詹姆斯·马森对本文做出了贡献。</p><p>写信给 Ian Lovett： <a href="mailto:ian.lovett@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">ian.lovet@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Tue, 08 Aug 2023 11:23:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/us-made-cluster-munitions-fuel-ukrainian-counteroffective-c45c305f</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/us-made-cluster-munitions-fuel-ukrainian-counteroffective-c45c305f<author><![CDATA[Ian Lovett]]></author><category> gfx-contrib</category><category>乌克兰</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>国家/公共安全</category><category>武装部队</category><category>风险新闻</category><category>军事行动</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>national</category><category>公安</category><category>武装部队</category><category>风险新闻</category><category>军事行动</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Dozens Die in China Floods as Typhoon Remnants Batter North]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> Nearly two weeks after making landfall, Doksuri still wreaks mayhem—and another storm is coming <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001117838"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=6B5B836E-22CB-4333-B82F-35159829AF0D&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fdozens-die-in-china-floods-as-typhoon-remnants-batter-north-aeeb7d69&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption"> Millions of people were displaced as record-breaking rainfall inundated Jilin province in northeastern China.这次暴雨是早些时候淹没北京地区的台风“多克苏里”的余波。 Photo: Yan Linyun/Zuma Press<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001117838"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/selina-cheng" itemprop="url" rel="author">Selina Cheng</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> Aug. 8, 2023 7:21 am ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/dozens-die-in-china-floods-as-typhoon-remnants-batter-north-aeeb7d69"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p> HONG KONG—Dozens of people died and millions more have been displaced after the remnants of Typhoon Doksuri battered China&#39;s northeast, dumping torrential rain and causing widespread flooding, according to local governments and state media.</p><p> The northeastern provinces of Jilin and Heilongjiang were the latest to feel the aftereffects from <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/beijing-area-hit-by-deadliest-flooding-in-a-decade-73c571fc?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">a storm that made landfall</a> nearly two weeks ago in Fujian, about 2,000 miles to the south. Beijing and the nearby major port city of Tianjin, as well as surrounding regions continued to suffer the aftermath from days of heavy rainfall, even though the weather in the Chinese capital on Tuesday was partly sunny—with no rain.</p><p> Millions of people living across swaths of China still face the risk of flooding from the heavy precipitation dumped by Doksuri as it ground north.第二场台风“卡农”在短暂威胁日本后，目前正在威胁中国东北地区。预计卡努将在未来几天袭击朝鲜半岛。</p><p> China&#39;s typically arid northeast may again expect torrential rain this weekend, after accumulating more than 100 millimeters, around 4 inches, of rainfall in some areas over five days last week, China&#39;s meteorological service said. That is more than a fifth of the annual average for Heilongjiang <strong>&nbsp;</strong> province. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-831431?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> A man wading through a flooded farm in China&#39;s Hebei province.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: TINGSHU WANG/REUTERS</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> Rising waters have been putting a strain on embankments and flood basins of the Songhua and Nen rivers in the northeast, the Ministry of Emergency Management said in a statement Monday.预计卡努的到来将使救援工作变得更加困难。</p><p> The central government has yet to release nationwide figures for the total number of people who have died, gone missing or have been displaced, 10 days after hundreds of counties and towns were submerged by the floods.</p><p> In Jilin, 14 people died, including three local officials, authorities said on social media Sunday.另一名官员失踪。一个城镇约有 10 万人受到洪水影响。当地政府在社交媒体上发帖称，该地区的四座水库继续泄水，以维持安全水位。</p><p> Heilongjiang, a major food-producing province, saw 160,000 people displaced and around 220,000 acres of agricultural land affected, the People&#39;s Daily reported Sunday.</p><p> Areas further south and surrounding Beijing and Hebei, an industrial province southwest near Beijing, were among the earliest to face the effects of the typhoon. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-831428?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Millions of people in Hebei province have been affected by the downpours.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: TINGSHU WANG/REUTERS</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> As the recent heavy rains feed into river systems, the port-city of Tianjin is bracing for floods by Wednesday even though the weather there has cleared, state media reported earlier. Around 80,000 people have been evacuated from their homes, the city&#39;s Bureau of Emergency Management reported Sunday.</p><p> Ten people from Hebei died and 18 were missing as of Saturday <strong>,</strong> according to state media.</p><p> Zhuozhou, in Hebei, was hit particularly hard. More than 130,000 of its 600,000 population were affected, state media reported last week.</p><p> The flooding also hit some manufacturing. Shenzhen-listed Aerospace Hi-Tech Holding Group said one of its factories in Zhuozhou&#39;s aeronautics industrial park suspended production because its equipment was underwater.</p><p> Around 3.4 million people from over 100 counties in Hebei province were affected by the downpours, including about 1.7 million people who were displaced as of Monday, according to state media. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-831430?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Debris clogged a street on the outskirts of Beijing on Monday.</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：Andy Wong/美联社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>As millions struggled to cope with the floods, a Hebei official drew public criticism after saying that the province should act as Beijing&#39;s buffer by holding water in its basins to reduce the strain on the capital.</p><p> State media reports and local government social-media releases focused on rescue and restoration efforts, giving detailed accounts of emergency supplies deployed. Reports by state-owned news agency Xinhua tallied the equipment deployed for the rescue mission in Zhuozhou, such as generators and trucks carrying drinking water.</p><p> Tens of thousands of troops from China&#39;s People&#39;s Liberation Army and paramilitary police were also deployed in the rescue efforts near Beijing, repairing roads and clearing riverbanks, the agency reported.</p><p> The social-media account for the government of Jilin published the number of households where electricity was restored, lamp posts that were repaired and packets of medication dropped from helicopters.</p><p> Write to Selina Cheng at <a href="mailto:selina.cheng@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">selina.cheng@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Tue, 08 Aug 2023 11:21:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/dozens-die-in-china-floods-as-typhoon-remnants-batter-north-aeeb7d69</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/dozens-die-in-china-floods-as-typhoon-remnants-batter-north-aeeb7d69<author><![CDATA[Selina Cheng]]></author><category> Media/Entertainment</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>Disasters/Accidents</category><category> Floods/Tidal Waves</category><category> Hurricanes/Typhoons</category><category> Storms</category><category> Natural Disasters</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>地区政治</category><category>风险新闻</category><category>Weather</category><category> SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>disasters</category><category> accidents</category><category> floods</category><category> tidal waves</category><category> hurricanes</category><category> typhoons</category><category> storms</category><category> natural disasters</category><category>政治</category><category>国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>地区政治</category><category>风险新闻</category><category>weather</category><category> media</category><category>娱乐</category></item></channel></rss>